<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Keen on Seeking Cooperation with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians are keen on
seeking cooperation with Egypt and views of President Hosni
Mubarak on the Mideast peace process, a senior Palestinian
official said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Egypt's Middle East News Agency, Palestinian
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath
said the two sides will examine the deadlock in the Mideast peace
process during the third session of the Palestinian-Egyptian
Higher Joint Committee.
</P>
<P>
Shaath blamed the stalemate on Israel's intransigence in the
peace march and failure to carry out the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel have been
stalled since December when Israel shelved the Wye accord after
implementing the first of the three-phased withdrawal from another
13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Shaath arrived here earlier in the day to co-chair the joint
committee session with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The committee session will give a momentum to the bilateral
trade and investment relations and activate the signed trade
agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The session will reflect the depth of the Palestinian-Egyptian
relation and the Palestinian National Authority's keenness on
enhancing cooperation with Egypt in the health, education,
industry, transportation and security domains, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will probe the establishment of a fair of
Egyptian products in July in the Palestinian self-rule areas and
organization of meetings for businessmen on both sides to promote
economic cooperation, the Palestinian official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
