<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Renews Rap on Iran's Occupation of Gulf Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) Rashid Bin Abdullah Al-Nuaimi
reiterated his country's rejection to Iran's recent actions on
three disputed Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
"The provocative and unjustified Iranian conducts pose a
danger to the region, threaten to cause instability and do not
serve the good neighborly ties between Iran and the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states," Al-Nuaimi said at the opening
session of the GCC foreign ministerial meeting in Saudi capital
Riyadh Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Nuaimi rebuffed Iran's establishment of a municipal office
and an educational complex on Abu Moussa island in February,
saying Tehran was seeking "to impose all illegal de facto
situation and solidify its occupation of the islands by means of
changing their demographic status."
</P>
<P>
"All these measures are deemed invalid," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both the UAE and Iran claimed sovereignty over the islands of
Abu Moussa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs, which are located near the
strategic shipping lanes at the mouth of the Gulf and potentially
oil-rich.
</P>
<P>
Iran has controlled the islands since 1971 after Britain ended
its protectorate. Tehran rejects international arbitration over
the islands and has so far offered negotiations on Abu Moussa
alone.
</P>
<P>
It has recently conducted massive military exercises near Abu
Moussa, which prompted strong protest from the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The UAE had called for an extraordinary meeting of the GCC
foreign ministers on March 4 to discuss the Iranian drills.
</P>
<P>
The GCC ministers condemned in a joint statement the maneuvers
and called on Tehran to end its occupation of the three islands.
</P>
<P>
These war games "will not help in confidence building because
they violate the UAE sovereignty and is an attempt by the Iranian
side to dedicate its occupation" of the three islands, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi strongly
criticized the GCC statement, saying it is "a source of regret and
certainly dose not help solve the disputes."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi called on UAE officials to go to Tehran for talks
over the islands. "We have always called on the UAE to discuss
the problems between us in bilateral talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today all problems can be solved through dialogue, but not
through intimidation and propaganda," Kharrazi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
