<HEADLINE> U.S. Jet Ignores Italian Rules Before Tragedy: Procuratorate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 14 (Xinhua) -- An Italian military procuratorate
confirmed Sunday that the American plane was making an
unauthorized flight when it cut a cable at a ski resort in
northern Italy, killing 20 people.
</P>
<P>
The EA-6B reconnaissance plane was among those military jets
that were forbidden by the Italian government to enter some areas
including the resort of Cavalese, the chief procurator said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Italy asked NATO planes except F-16s not to enter
the above-mentioned areas because local people often grumbled
about their awful noise.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government and military have not confirmed the
procuratorate's statement so far. However, local press said that
the Italian military indeed sent such a message to the NAT0
command, but failed to receive any response.
</P>
<P>
The pilot, Captain Richard Ashby, was cleared earlier this
month of 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter and other related
charges in a court-martial at Camp Lejeune in North Carolina. The
result enraged the Italian public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
