<HEADLINE> Israel Reiterates Position Over Talks With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Moshe
Arens reiterated on Sunday that the peace talks with Syria should
be resumed without any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a tour in the town of Abu Gosh
near Jerusalem, Arens said that the resumption of the
negotiations is totally dependent on Syria.
</P>
<P>
Arens said that if Syria sticks to its position that Israel
must give up all of the Golan Heights, the talks will not be
resumed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace talks broke off in February 1996 and
efforts to rekindle them have stumbled over the issue of the
Golan Heights captured by Israel in the 1967 war and later
annexed to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants negotiations to be resumed where they left off
under Israel's former Labor government - with an agreement in
principle for a return of the Golan in exchange for security
guarantees and a full peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
But the Likud government, which came to power in 1996,
has refused to be tied to the Labor government's stance and
insisted that the peace talks should be resumed without any
preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
that he hoped to sign a peace agreement with Syria by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
But Syria has dismissed Netanyahu's remarks as "an election
propaganda," as Israel will hold early general elections on
May 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
