<HEADLINE> EU States Differ on Agenda 2000 Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign
ministers ended a meeting Sunday with differing views on progress
made in resolving crucial Agenda 2000 finances disputes.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer
said that the meeting has "made a decisive progress." and "I have
the compromise figures right in front of my eyes," added Fischer
who hosted the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, Wolfgang Schuessel, Austrian foreign minister, noted
that Fischer was putting too positive a spin on this meeting,
saying that "in the nuts an bolts of it there are still big
differences."
</P>
<P>
The so-called Agenda 2000 is a package including the EU's
budget, farm subsidies and structural aid which extends mainly to
poorer southern member states of the EU.
</P>
<P>
A farm spending compromise was agreed last Thursday but the
Austrian foreign minister said it was only firmly backed by 11 of
the bloc's 15 members..
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine cautioned that "the
assessment of the comprise is not over."
</P>
<P>
"Reservations are not just about money but also over its
contents," said Vedrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
