<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU States Differ on Agenda 2000 Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- With a deadline looming in less than
two weeks, European Union (EU) foreign ministers ended a meeting
Sunday with firmly differing views on progress made in resolving
crucial Agenda 2000 spending disputes.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said at a press
conference after the meeting that it had "made a decisive
progress." "I have the compromise figures right in front of my
eyes," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel dampened this
view. He told reporters he believed Fischer was putting too
positive a spin on this meeting. He also said, "In the nuts and
bolts of it there are still big differences."
</P>
<P>
The so-called Agenda 2000 is a package including the EU's
budget, farm subsidies and structural aid which flows mainly to
poorer southern member states of the EU.
</P>
<P>
A farm spending compromise was agreed last Thursday but
Schuessel said it was only firmly backed by 11 of the bloc's 15
members.
</P>
<P>
Farm ministers overshot the prescribed average annual farm
spending level of U.S. 44.6 billion dollars by some 1 billion
dollars per year for the period 2000 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said Paris had not yet
concluded its evaluation of the deal. "Reservations are not just
about money but also over its contents," he said.
</P>
<P>
Big differences at this foreign ministers meeting remained over
how to fund the EU's budget from 2000 to 2006. "We are far apart
from a solution," Fischer admitted. Schuessel also said, "This is
a difficult topic; we are not at the end of the tunnel."
</P>
<P>
Current EU financial arrangements expire at the end of this
year. Germany, the biggest contributions-nation of the EU, is
demanding a cut to its budget contribution.
</P>
<P>
But Britain firmly opposes the negotiations over his
multi-billion dollar annual EU rebate, as demanded by Germany. "We
have no interest in negotiating away the British rebate," said
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Setting structural and cohesion aid levels to southern EU
countries such as Spain, Portugal and Greece as well as Ireland
remains the other key issue of dispute.
</P>
<P>
Southern states want current levels of structural and cohesion
fund aid to be retained. Northern states, like Germany, are
calling for cuts.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said it was clear Portugal and Ireland had special
problems in this area and that they could not be left in the
lurch.
</P>
<P>
EU states were divided in three blocs on structural funds with
one-third wanting to spend 276 billion dollars in the period from
2000 to 2006, one-third backing 220 billion dollars and the final
third seeking less than 220 billion dollars, according to
Schuessel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
