<HEADLINE> Lafontaine: He Quits Over "Poor Teamwork" in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Oskar Lafontaine, who last week
resigned as German finance minister and chairman of its ruling
Social Democratic party (SPD), said Sunday that "poor teamwork" in
the government had compelled him to leave.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine made this first remark to reporters outside his home
in the Saarland region since he quit Thursday following a policy
clash with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
"I left because of the poor teamwork that we displayed over
recent months. You cannot work successfully if the teamwork is not
up to scratch," Lafontaine told the German Television ARD.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine said his decision to quit had nothing to do with the
political direction of the Schroeder government "and what we have
achieved in the last few months."
</P>
<P>
Explaining his three days of public silence after stepping
down, something which puzzled commentators, Lafontaine said he had
needed time to come to terms with the decision to resign all his
political posts.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that will be understood by anyone who appreciates
what a decision like that means," He said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
