<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Never Accept Confederation in Cyprus: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides Sunday reiterated that he will never accept the
establishment of a confederation on the Cyprus island.
</P>
<P>
He described the regime set up by the Turkish Cypriots in
northern Cyprus as illegal and called on the international
community to exercise its influence on the Turkish side so that it
displays a more constructive attitude.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remarks at a memorial service of a Cypriot
fighter, who died in the struggle for Cyprus' independence from
the British colonial rule from 1955-59.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the international community is expected to step
up its efforts for the resumption of the Cyprus peace talks after
the April elections in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriot north and the
Greek Cypriot south since 1974 when Turkey landed its troops in
1974 and took over the northern third of the island after a failed
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has since maintained 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to
protect the Turkish Cypriots, who unilaterally declared in 1983
the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized
only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula, but the bilateral peace
talks have been stalled since summer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has said he will not
resume negotiations with the government unless his regime is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
He also said he will not negotiate for a federal solution.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the Greek Cypriot side is ready to participate in
all honesty and goodwill dialogue for a settlement based on
U.N. resolutions and within the framework set out by the
international organization.
</P>
<P>
Clerides criticized the Turkish side for "placing
insurmountable obstacles with its negative stance". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
