<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., British Warplanes Bomb Iraqi Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes
Sunday continued to bomb civilian facilities and military sites in
northern and southern Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the unnamed spokesman as saying
that at 8:50 a.m. (0550 GMT), 32 formations of U.S.-British
warplanes from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi
airspace over Dhi-Qar, Najaf, Muthana and Basra provinces.
</P>
<P>
These jets raided some civilian facilities and military sites
in Muthana province, said the spokesman, adding that Iraqi
anti-aircraft units fired back and forced them to flee.
</P>
<P>
At noon, 11 formations of enemy planes from Turkish
airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Erbil
and Mosul provinces and bombarded civilian installations and
military sites, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Confrontations between Iraqi air defenses and U.S.-British
warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones almost occurred every day
since the mid-December U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
after the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds
in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from what they
called "Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize the no-fly zones
and will fire at any allied warplanes violating its airspace.
</P>
</TEXT>
