<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Vows to Liberate Lebanon From Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Hezbollah's Secretary General
Hassan Nasrallah Sunday vowed that his group would continue its
resistance movement till the day when all Lebanese territory is
liberated from "Israeli enemies."
</P>
<P>
At a mass rally in southern suburb of Beirut on the occasion of
the 21st anniversary of Israeli invasion of Lebanon, he warned
Israel not to launch a large massive offensive against his
country, saying any aggression will have the same result of
failure.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people across Lebanon held various demonstrations
against Israeli occupation on the same day.
</P>
<P>
In the country's eastern area of Hirmel, demonstrators burned
Israeli flags and chanted anti-Israeli slogans. They asked Israel
to comply with the United Nations Resolution 425 without
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's commemoration came two weeks after Israeli forces
suffered the heaviest losses in more than one year in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In less than a week last month, a total of seven Israeli
soliders, including a general, were killed in Hezbollah
guerrillas' ambushes.
</P>
<P>
On March 14, 1978, Israel launched first major invasion of
Lebanon with the claimed aim of avenging a raid by forces of the
Palestinian National Liberation Movement, the main guerrilla group
within the Palestinian Liberation Organization that headquartered
in south Lebanon at the time.
</P>
<P>
Four days later, the U.N. Security Council adopted the
resolution 425 calling for an immediate and unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
After Palestinian guerrillas left Lebanon, Israel set up a
self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly
prevent its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah has been fighting to evict Israeli
occupation forces and its ally South Lebanon Army out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Many Israelis favor a unilateral Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon, but the country's senior officials, including Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, insisted that a withdrawal must be
applied before a negotiated agreement with Lebanese government
over providing security guarantee for its north after the pullout.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, which was first made by Israel
last April, asking the Jewish state to fully comply with the
resolution 425 without any conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
