<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-14 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Urged to Adopt Positive Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Presidential Political
Adviser Osama el-Baz Sunday called on Sudan to adopt "a positive
policy" toward other countries.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz made the call at a gathering at the Egyptian Cultural
Club, which was organized by Egypt's Former Prime Minister Abdel
Aziz Hegazi.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz said Egypt aspires for a "strong and stable" Sudan, one
that adopts "a positive foreign policy" toward neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt wants an independent and strong Sudan, not a subordinate
one," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"All what concerns Egypt is that the Sudanese government
changes its present policies that only express the will of a small
group within the Islamic Front under Hassan al Turabi," he said.
</P>
<P>
El-Baz maintained that the influence of al Turabi, speaker of
the Sudanese National Assembly (Parliament), on the government has
given rise to "dangerous and anti-Egypt policies."
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative" that Sudan restores its role in the region
and cooperation with neighboring countries, he said, adding
that "everything that is in the interest of Sudan is also in the
interest of Egypt."
</P>
<P>
The relations between Egypt and Sudan soured in 1995 after
Cairo accused Khartoum of masterminding an assassination attempt
on President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also blamed Sudan for harboring Muslim extremists who
attempted to topple Mubarak's secular government and install a
strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
There have been indications of a thaw in the relations between
Sudan and Egypt after the two Arab neighbors expressed willingness
and took steps to forge ahead reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
