<HEADLINE> 2 Wounded in Bomb Blast in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Two people were wounded Sunday
night in a bomb blast in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, which had been planted under a truck, went off at
Yenibosna Deereyolu Street of Bahcelievler district in Istanbul,
injuring two people, with one in serious condition, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest in a series of terrorist attacks recently.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, 13 people were killed and six others wounded when
three unidentified assailants hurled a Molotov cocktail in a "Blue
Market" in Goztepe district in Kadikoy of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, a bomb planted between two cars exploded in
Gaziosmanpasa district of Istanbul, but caused no casualty.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a group of attackers threw a Molotov
cocktail and set a bus on fire in Arabayatagi district of western
province of Bursa, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
On March 5, Cankiri Governor Ayhan Cevik was seriously wounded
in a bomb blast in republic district in the city of Cankiri, in
which three people were killed and nine others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The bomb attacks were believed to be launched in protest of
the arrest of Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party, which has been fighting since 1984 a guerrilla war
for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
