<HEADLINE> Tanzania Calls for Equal Economic Order in 21st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 14 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa Sunday urged the rich nations to cooperate with the poor in
an effort to create a competitive but equitable economic order as
the world enters the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The economic and social justice are of great importance to the
development of the poor nations, Mkapa said, in an interview with
Diplomacy, a monthly magazine published in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
According to an official press release, Mkapa demanded that the
 international community not carry with it the "baggage of bad
things" of this century like wars and insecurity into the coming
century.
</P>
<P>
He expressed deep concern over the weak economies which are
often asked to open up to transnational conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
"But when the interests of the strong economies are at state
they impose restrictions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa observed that the free market by its nature always favors
the strong against the weak.
</P>
<P>
"To ask Tanzania to compete with the United States, for
instance, is a joke to say the least," the press release quoted
the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
On problems facing Tanzania, Mkapa said the challenges are not
political, social, security or lack of natural resources, but
development of financial, technical, and marketing capacity
necessary to transform those resources into tangible aspects of
economic growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
