<HEADLINE> Mobutu's Former Ally Becomes Minister in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- President of the war-ridden
Democratic Republic of Congo, Laurent Kabila, formed his new
government Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The most prominent of the government reshuffle is the new
Economy and Industry Minister, Bemba Saolona.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, Saolona, a former ally of
late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko's associate and business tycoon,
was announced to take the key position in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Saolona's son is reported heading a guerrilla movement fighting
to topple Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Ministry was assigned to Kabila's Chief of
Staff, Abdoulaye Yerodia Ndombasi.
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Minister Jean-Charles Okoto was re-named as a
regional governor two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mawampanga Mwana Nanga retained his post, as
did Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo and Interior Minister Gaetan
Kakudji.
</P>
<P>
Pierre-Victor Mpoyo, a senior Kabila aide who has held a
non-specific cabinet rank, was named Petroleum Minister.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who came to power in the central African country after
he drove out Mobutu in 1997, has been engaged in war against
rebels since last August. He dissolved his cabinet on February 20.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
