<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President-Elect Ends Kenyan Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President-elect Olusegun
Obasanjo Monday urged Kenyan businessmen to increase trade with
his country.
</P>
<P>
He made the call while addressing some 150 Kenyan and Nigerian
businessmen at the Grand Regency Hotel here after wining in the
general election last month.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo met with Kenyan Assistant Minister Antony Ndilinge of
Trade and spoke at the conference before he left here for Cairo at
noon after winding up his short visit to Kenya Monday to continue
his first foreign tour.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi met the Nigerian
president-elect at the State House Monday morning and saw him off
at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader told the businessmen that the trade between
Kenya and Nigeria should be enhanced, and businessmen of both
countries should have more dialogs and talk together to explore
potential in trade in various areas.
</P>
<P>
He asked Kenya to increase the number of civil air flights to
Nigeria from the present three flights a week and increase the
volume of cargo shipment as well.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo also noted that Nigeria will be a democratic and
civilian nation, not a military one, after he become president on
May 29, saying that other African countries should accept
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian President-elect came to Kenya on Sunday evening
after his hours-long visit to Mozambique. It is reported that
Obasanjo will also visit other countries in Asia and Europe, and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
