<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore FM on Relations With Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 15 (Xinhua)-- Singapore Minister for Foreign
Affairs and Law S. Jayakumar affirmed Monday that his country will
continue to work with Indonesia, both bilaterally and within
ASEAN, to further strengthen relations to the benefit of both
countries.
</P>
<P>
In his remarks to Parliament Monday, Jayakumar said, "We will
establish rational and stable long-term relations with Indonesia
as we have done in the past 30 years, a relationship based on
mutual respect and equality between two independent countries."
</P>
<P>
Recalling recent developments in the relations between the two
neighbors, Jayakumar said Singapore first proposed Multilateral
Trade Finance Guarantee scheme to help Indonesia tide over the
crisis and after most Indonesia's trading partners preferred their
own bilateral schemes Singapore subsequently offered its own
Bilateral Trade Financing Guarantee scheme.
</P>
<P>
Singapore also announced in July 1998 humanitarian aid package
to Indonesia in the form of rice and medicines, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar said the current difficulties in Indonesia have also
not stopped his country from investing in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On criticism made against Singapore, Jayakumar conceded
relations between Singapore and Indonesia are going through a
difficult period as various leaders and officials have made
allegations and negative comments against Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"It is pointless to give detailed rebuttal of all the various
allegations that have been made in an off-hand manner without
supporting facts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let me restate that Singapore has a vested interest in
Indonesia's stability, growth and prosperity. Indonesia is a close
neighbor and a major trading partner. An Indonesian setback hurt
its neighbors, including Singapore," he said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting what Singapore Senior Minister lee Kuan Yew and Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong commented recently on the allegations and
criticism against Singapore, Jayakumar said, "In the run-up to the
Indonesian parliamentary elections in June 1999 and the
presidential elections later this year, we can expect more
allegations to be directed against us."
</P>
<P>
"But we would avoid being drawn into their politics," he said.
"Singapore would try to avoid being a party in Indonesia's
domestic elections."
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar reaffirmed that the Singapore government is prepared
to work with whoever becomes the president of Indonesia and forms
the next government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
