<HEADLINE> Pak, U.S. Officials Begin Talks on Exports Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and the United States
opened talks here Monday on ways and means to curb exports of
sensitive nuclear material to third country.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that a three-member U.S. delegation met
Pakistan's Customs officials and those from the Central Board of
Revenue and discussed with them ways and means to tighten control
over exports of nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
Details of the talks are not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan said last Saturday it had issued a Statutory
Regulatory Order (SRO) to control the export of nuclear technology
to any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The SRO reveals new regulations under which nuclear technology
can not be transferred to any other country without the no
objection certificate of the Pakistan Atomic Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan detonated nuclear devices in May last year, and since
then the government has repeatedly said that Pakistan will not
transfer its nuclear technology to any other country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
