<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Deports More War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada has deported more than 20
torturers, death-squad members and corrupt officials from brutal
regimes in the last eight months as part of a crackdown on
suspected modern-day war criminals.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Department is trying to change the country's
reputation as a safe haven for undesirables to a place where
vigilant officials hunt down and remove people with villainous
pasts, the National Post newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Craig Goodes, head of the department's war crimes unit, was
quoted as saying that about 200 of 400 old files have been
reviewed and about 200 new cases opened since last July, leaving
the department with a total of about 400 files still open.
</P>
<P>
Goodes said officials in Canadian posts in Central Africa and
the former Yugoslavia have also prevented about 40 suspected war
criminals from coming into Canada.
</P>
<P>
War crimes include murder, extermination, enslavement,
kidnapping and assault or robbery against a civilian population or
identifiable group of persons.
</P>
<P>
He said the Immigration Department is no longer content merely
to remove suspected war criminals who have already been identified,
but will ferret out those hiding in the community.
</P>
<P>
It's a lofty goal for a department that has come under fire in
recent years for failing to remove people suspected of torture and
murder.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, an internal report noted that 324 alleged modern-day
war criminals remained at large in Canada and only about 80 had
been removed in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
