<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Meeting on Social Development Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 350 delegates from 24 east
and southern African countries gathered here to review the
progress made on social development since the Copenhagen World
Summit in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The conference will provide an opportunity for countries to
share experiences, challenges and how countries have addressed the
problem of poverty," Kenyan Minister for Planning and National
Development George Saitoti said in his welcome address.
</P>
<P>
In the three-day meeting sponsored by the U.N. Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) and United Nations Development Program
(UNDP), policy-makers, leaders of non-governmental and
inter-governmental organizations will scrutinize the progress in
reducing poverty, creating jobs, enhancing social integration and
fostering stable and just societies.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to the average annual rate of GDP growth of only one
percent for the two years preceding the Summit, the rate of GDP
growth increased to 3.2 percent as an average for the four years
after the summit," Deputy Executive Secretary Lalla Barka of the
ECA said.
</P>
<P>
"However, given Africa's high birth rate, these achievements
fall far short of the required growth rate to reduce poverty by
half by the year 2015. According to ECA's estimate, eight percent
for East Africa region and six percent for Southern Africa region
are required to achieve this objective," Barka said.
</P>
<P>
Studies show that poverty, unemployment, social disintegration,
 conflict and environmental degradation is on the increase in east
and southern Africa. The gap between the rich and the poor
continues to grow, with Africa accounting for a large percentage
of over one billion people in the world living in abject poverty.
</P>
<P>
At the World Summit in Copenhagen, Denmark, African countries
joined the rest of the world in proclaiming that they would give
social development a top priority among their national policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
