<HEADLINE> Brain Drain Continues in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Crime and violence continue
to drive South Africa's key specialists and managers out of the
country, according to the findings of an independent survey
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted among over 55,000 employees from
organizations across the economic spectrum, showed that about 10
percent of turnover among specialists and management staff were
attributed to emigration.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of those who resigned to emigrate gave the crime
rate as a reason for emigration, and 47 percent cited violence,
according to the survey conducted by human resource consultants
FSA-Contact.
</P>
<P>
These were almost the same as last year's survey findings.
</P>
<P>
Falling living standards, health and education, affirmative
action policies in South Africa and better employment
opportunities abroad were also cited as reasons.
</P>
<P>
Most of those leaving, or 38 percent, emigrated to the United
States while 26 percent went to Britain, the survey showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
