<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan PM Denies Genocide Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Prime Minister Pierre
Celestin Rwigema has denied any involvement in the 1994 genocide,
the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema said that some people had wanted to tarnish his image
which is generally good. He claimed that he himself is a
"genocide survivor,'' and that he ''narrowly escaped death" during
the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters recently, the prime minister blamed the
resurfacing of the accusations from his political foes in the
party, particularly four MPs who had been axed a week ago from
parliament on charges of high treason and fostering the Hutu
extremist ideology, reported the RNA, in a special story faxed to
Xinhua in Nairobi here.
</P>
<P>
More than 500,000 people in Rwanda, primarily Tutsis and
moderate Hutus, were brutally massacred in a genocide that took
place in April to June of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema defended himself saying that the allegations were
leveled by Amri Karekezi, the former head of Biryogo sector near
capital Kigali, who had allegedly stolen three vehicles of the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
To seek vengeance, Karekezi had accused Rwigema of distributing
arms to the marauding Hutu gangs, and making lists of people to
kill, Rwigema said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Rwigema's alleged involvement in the genocide has
raised a hot debate about some civil and military officials
suspected to have taken part in the genocide and other crimes
against humanity, which were committed in Rwanda in 1959 and in
the years which followed, but who are still free.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, there were reports saying that judicial sources in
Kigali that a file about the prime minister had been opened and
that investigations were nearing completion. However, government
sources said the reports were distorted.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Minister of Information Augustin
Iyamuremye on Monday said that there was no case filed against the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Pierre Celestin Rwigema was appointed to the post of prime
minister since August 1995 and is chairman of the Democratic
Republican (MDR) Party, since July 1998.  During all that time,
no judicial action was undertaken in the framework of genocide and
massacres which rocked Rwanda in 1994,'' he was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
