<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Writethrough Premier Upset by Anti-China Current, Hopes for Good U.S. Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said
here today that despite an anti-China current emerging in the
United States, he is still looking forward to a successful trip to
the country early next month for the restoration of the good
momentum of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks at a press conference here today following
the conclusion of the Second Session of the Ninth National People'
s Congress.
</P>
<P>
Sino-U.S. relations have been victimized by internal conflicts
in the United States, he pointed out, noting that he expects to
encounter some "hostile or unfriendly atmosphere" during his
coming visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I noted that in the February 22 issue of Business Week, there
is an article titled: China, What's Going Wrong?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Business Week article depicted China as being
plagued by serious disasters, Zhu said that the story is "very
special."
</P>
<P>
"So far I have never seen any other article of this kind
appearing in the U.S. media. In fact, it reflects the current. The
Sino-U.S. relations have been victimized by internal struggle in
the U.S.," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that under such an atmosphere, his trip to the United
States next month is aimed at presenting a true picture about
China and restoring the good momentum of a constructive strategic
partnership between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said jokingly that he himself is a victim of the bad
atmosphere in the United States, because a photo at the cover of
the Business Week makes him "look like a dead man."
</P>
<P>
Zhu said he is fully aware that under such a bad atmosphere his
task during the trip will not be easy, and some media predicted
that his trip could not possibly be successful.
</P>
<P>
"But I will continue to go on this trip," he said, adding that
since some people in the United States have anger and complaints,
he would let them to vent their anger and complaints.
</P>
<P>
On the so-called "spy case" in which China has allegedly
obtained nuclear secrets from the United States, he said it is
like a tale from the Arabian Nights.
</P>
<P>
"I think that on this issue some Americans have made two
mistakes due to underestimation," he said, noting that those
Americans have underestimated the ability of the United States to
keep secret.
</P>
<P>
The Los Alamos Lab has a very strict control system to keep
secret and so far no evidence has been found to support the
allegation that Wen Ho Lee had stolen military secrets, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Those Americans have also underestimated China's ability in
research and development of military technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people are very intelligent and diligent, Zhu said,
adding that "China is now fully capable of developing any kind of
military technology and it is only a matter of time."
</P>
<P>
"So, why should we put ourselves under political and moral
risks to steal military technology?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhu said that the United States has overestimated the
so-called "threat."
</P>
<P>
"Since all the most sophisticated weapons are originated from
the Unites States, what does it need for the United States to be
afraid of?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said he believes that during his forthcoming visit to the
United States, he could get a warm welcome instead of "walking
into a minefield." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
