<HEADLINE> Latin American Economies Grow by 2.5 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Asian and Russian
financial crises and falling commodity prices, compounded by
natural disasters, took their toll in Latin America in 1998,
resulting in a slowdown of growth to 2.5 percent compared to 5.2
percent in 1997, the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 Annual Report, the Washington-based IDB blamed the
slowdown on such negative factors as reduced exports and capital
inflows, as well as higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said the "fundamentals for future growth
remained solidly in place; not only was macroeconomic stability
preserved, but a commitment to market refrom was maintained, and
even deepened, in the region."
</P>
<P>
Inflation remained under control, at a median rate of less than
10 percent, on a par with 1997, and "fiscal and monetary policies
were aimed at curtailing the fiscal imbalances and preventing
foreign exchange disequilibria," the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the IDB's 40th Annual Meeting scheduled for March 15-17
in Paris, France, its board of governors will review the Annual
Report as well as analyze the evolution of the region's economies
and their financial needs.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Ecuador and Venezuela were particularly hard hit by
the fall in oil prices and Chile's export revenues declined 14
percent, or 3 percent of the country's gross domestic product, as
a result of falling commodity prices, mainly copper, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Total capital inflows to the region dropped to 64 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998 compared to 79 billion dollars the previous year,
and the "yield on Latin American debt issues in the Euro-markets
doubled between July and September from 456 basis points to 900
points. Toward the end of the year, the average yield had fallen
substantially, but was still above its initial level."
</P>
<P>
"Uncertainty and volatility pushed interest rates upwards," the
report said. "By October, interest rates had practically doubled
in several countries with respect to the levels observed in late
1997."
</P>
<P>
Among the other repercussions in the region were falling
international reserves, rising public sector deficits, falling
stock markets values, and the tightening of fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
Latin America and the Caribbean continued on the path of reform
despite the shocks, the report said. Tariff codes changed little
during the crisis and the "commitment to economic integration with
the rest of the world was maintained." Several countries
strengthened financial supervision and regulation and introduced
major tax reforms, and privatization continued, although "at a
move moderate pace than previous years."
</P>
<P>
Assessing the outlook, the report said the region could benefit
from "expected improvement in Asian performance" as well as growth
in the United States and Europe, although "the possibility of new
eruptions cannot be dismissed." Because of depressed levels of
commodity prices, "continued fiscal and monetary prudence will
certainly be key factors," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the IDB's lending activities in 1998, the report said
that the bank "responded quickly and effectively" with a record 10
billion dollars in lending to help the region counteract natural
catastrophes and world economic challenges. Disbursements also
reached a new record of 6.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said that for the fifth consecutive year the IDB
"remained the region's main source of multilateral credit,
bolstering the Latin American and Caribbean economies in their
effort to alleviate poverty, build infrastructure and increase
productivity, support the private sector, and reform
institutions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
