<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Adopt Smart Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Primary Industries
Minister Lim Keng Yaik Monday stressed the need for the country to
adopt smart farming in order to ease agricultural work load which
he said is imposing a burden on the government.
</P>
<P>
Smart farming means agricultural activities combined with
knowledge and information.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture with knowledge would increase a plantation's
expertise for maximum production with minimum cost and is
environment-friendly, he said at the National Conference on
"Engineering Smart Farming Towards the Next Millennium" here.
</P>
<P>
Lim said that with the implementation of smart farming,
economies of scale was greatly needed, and as such efforts towards
the enlargement of agricultural areas through the integration of
smaller-sized lands, creation of estates and group work needed to
be carried out to ensure an effective operation.
</P>
<P>
He said that to realize the smart farming concept, the
development of human resources was also important and farmers
should be given adequate training.
</P>
<P>
The minister called upon private and public sector training
institutes to play their role in training farmers and plantation
managers so that agricultural programs and activities planned
could be implemented effectively.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector not only produces food but also
non-food products like rubber, Lim said, adding that in 1998,
Malaysia exported commodities and commodities-based goods worth
49.8 million ringgit (13.105 million U.S. dollars), an increase of
30.7 percent from the previous year, and amounting to 17.4
percent of the country's total exports.
</P>
<P>
But in the food sector, Malaysia had to import foodstuffs worth
more than 10 billion ringgit (2.631 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998,
Lim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
