<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Cut Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh announced here Monday that Iran is to reduce its oil
output ceiling in line with the recent agreement reached by major
oil producers.
</P>
<P>
However, Zanganeh did not specify the amount his country would
reduce. Iran currently produces more than 3.6 million barrels each
day, above its 3.3-million-barrels-per-day quota set by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency, the
minister said all the OPEC members but Iraq would cut about 22.9
million barrels of crude per day following the reduction decision.
</P>
<P>
Four major oil producers, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela and
Mexico, agreed Friday in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, to cut their
output ceiling by more than 2 million barrels per day in an
attempt to bolster oil prices. The accords takes effect on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, Iran compromised on March 7 after months of
wrangling with Saudi Arabia, agreeing to make any further
production cuts from its current output of 3.6 million barrels a
day.
</P>
<P>
It had argued that 3.925 million barrels per day should be
recognized as the baseline for any cuts.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative on production cuts ended a year-long oil
price slump and reports said that benchmark Brent crude rose to
13.8 U.S. dollars on Monday from 12-year lows.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh said the period for enforcement of the agreement would
be set by the OPEC members in their future session on March 23.
The OPEC members have reached the conclusion that adoption of
joint measures is more important than engaging in disputes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that recent agreement would help stabilize
the oil market through creating a balance between output and
demand.
</P>
<P>
The stability of oil market, from both long-term and short-term
views, will be in the interests of the oil producing countries,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The recent agreement is hailed here as heralding the end of the
"fourth oil shock," which started in 1997 and worsened in 1998 due
to a glut in OPEC output, coupled with slacken demands and the
financial crisis in southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Some oil experts here predict that oil price can reach as high
as 20 dollars per barrel if the agreement would be observed by the
OPEC members in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
