<HEADLINE> Tibetan Exhibition Attracting Foreign Experts -2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 9-day exhibition shows regional development, treasures,
cultural and religious items, clothing, decorative art, and modern
paintings and has had a large number of visitors since it opened a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
Israel Epstein, the 84-year-old Poland-born expert who has
spent most of his life living and working in China, attended the
exhibition in his wheelchair and said he was very happy to be
there. He's been to Tibet 4 times, and things changed each time.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes Tibet's development is limited by its
geological and climatic conditions, but in recent years, it has
made progress faster than at any time in its history.
</P>
<P>
A Russian expert working for Xinhua also saw changes in the
photos of Tibet. He went to Tibet in 1987 and that kindled a
strong interest in Tibetan history and culture. But that was more
than ten years ago, he says, and the photos here show the
development that has taken place, and the greater number of
buildings and entertainment facilities like cinemas.
</P>
<P>
He says he's planning a visit to Tibet again in 2 years, and
this time, he will take his son, a twelve-year-old who is studying
back in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
