<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Vice President Visits Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Senior Vice President and chief
economist of the World Bank (WB) Joseph Stiglitz ended his
three-day visit to Bangladesh Monday after discussing financial
reform and other issues with Bangladeshi officials and scholars.
</P>
<P>
"There is no simple formula, no single recipe...what is
required is balance," Stiglitz said at one of his public lectures
on economic development in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"The state should have more than a minimalist role, but less
than an all-encompassing role," he said. "The private sector still
should be the focus of development with the government providing
appropriate institutional infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here Monday afternoon, Stiglitz said that
the non-governmental organizations in Bangladesh play an important
role in improving the life of the poor people.
</P>
<P>
"The commitment to reform (of the Bangladeshi government) is
essential to development," and "competition within and outside the
government should be promoted," which was essential to success, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria said that the relations
between the Bangladesh and the WB were the best at present. The
commitment of loans of the WB to Bangladesh this year was about 1
billion U.S. dollars, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
