<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Designate Firewood Substitute Fuel Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is considering to
designate the year 2000-2001 as another Firewood Substitute Fuel
Year and adopt cost effective systems for wide use of the
substitute fuel in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Briquette is being introduced as one of the firewood substitute
fuel in the country's efforts to prevent forest depletion and
preserve the nation's forests and environment.
</P>
<P>
A factory has been set up in Yangon by the Myanmar Forestry
Ministry to produce briquette and its extension use as a firewood
substitute fuel is being pushed.
</P>
<P>
Such factories are also planned for other divisions like
Sagaing, Mandalay and Magway divisions where arid districts lie.
</P>
<P>
Firewood, along with charcoal, has been used in Myanmar with an
annual consumption of more than 24 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Indiscriminate felling and cutting of trees including firewood
plantations for fuel and burning of charcoal have been known as
the cause of forest depletion in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The country has worked out projects for greening the arid
districts under which revival of firewood plantations is among the
measures taken.
</P>
<P>
To prevent forest depletion, Myanmar also applies micro-wave
ovens and agricultural wastes for fuel.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar once designated 1995 as the Firewood Substitute Fuel
Year and progress was reportedly made in the implementation plan,
while endeavors were then made for greening of the nine arid
districts.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's forest area is reducing year after year, dropping by
7 percent compared with 36 years ago. The 1962 data showed that 57
percent of the country's total area was then covered by forests.
The percentage dropped to 50 in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
