<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seeks Manila Support for Attending EU-ASEAN Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Myanmar Foreign Minister
Win Aung is expected to meet Philippine Vice President Gloria
Arroyo and other officials to seek support for Myanmar's
participation in an EU-ASEAN meeting, government officials said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Win Aung arrived here Sunday for a three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
Win Aung already met his Philippine counterpart Domingo Siazon
late Sunday. His meeting with Vice President Arroyo and other
officials have also been arranged, officials said.
</P>
<P>
After Sunday's meeting with Siazon, the Myanmar minister told
reporters that members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) should remain tightly united.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN "won't be complete without a member," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If ASEAN is united, nobody could come and then make a wedge
between us," he added. "We should stick together come what may."
</P>
<P>
Siazon said that "what is being requested is to discriminate
against an ASEAN member, which is unthinkable."
</P>
<P>
Siazon also said that the meeting between the ASEAN and the
European Union (EU) has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan is
negotiating with the EU in an attempt to reach a compromise that
would allow the meeting to proceed as scheduled in Berlin,
Germany, on March 30.
</P>
<P>
The EU has opposed Myanmar's inclusion in the meeting of the
ASEAN and European foreign ministers in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar joined the ASEAN in 1997 along with Laos. Other members
of the ASEAN are Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Win Aung's Southeast Asia tour will also take him to Vietnam
and Laos at the conclusion of his visit to the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
