<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Man Gets 7 Years For Copyright Infringement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A court in the Chinese capital
today sentenced a man to 7 years in jail for copyright
infringement, the heaviest sentence ever handed down for this
crime in China.
</P>
<P>
The man, Dai Guanghao, was also fined 150,000 yuan by the
Beijing First Intermediate People's Court, which found him guilty
of illegally printing more than 155,00 sets of the Chinese
Children's Encyclopedia at a printing factory in the Beijing
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Dai sold about 10,000 sets of the books for some 2.3 million
yuan. The remainder were confiscated by the court.
</P>
<P>
In related events, a farmer from east China's Anhui Province
was sentenced by the same court to 15 years in prison for
smuggling pornographic discs.
</P>
<P>
Li Qingtao was caught by police with 2,500 pornographic discs
on November 6, 1998. The police later found 3,500 more discs in
his house.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Beijing authorities have
confiscated 8,600 copies of illegal publications and 100,000
illegal discs since early March and have arrested at least 10
people in the drive against illegal publishing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
