<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Oldest Air Carrier Celebrates 58th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Flag carrier Philippine Airlines
(PAL) Monday marked its 58th anniversary which coincides with
another milestone in its climb back to full recovery - the
deadline for the submission of a revised rehabilitation plan to
the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC).
</P>
<P>
The company considers the twin events - its birth anniversary
and the submission for the approval of the new recovery plan -
significant because the plan "carries the seeds of our future
growth and success."
</P>
<P>
In a special message to the company officials and employees,
Lucio Tan, PAL chairman, said, "We are confident that today will
be a turning point in the history of PAL."
</P>
<P>
The past year was the most difficult in the history of Asia's
oldest air carrier, having to be closed for a brief spell because
of financial crunch brought about by internal problems aggravated
by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The trails of the past year are still fresh in our minds as we
mark our anniversary today. I take this occasion to express my
heartfelt gratitude for your selfless efforts to keep PAL flying,
particularly during its most difficult hours," Tan added.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the country's flag carrier hit its lowest bottom. PAL
witnessed some of the most turbulent events in its history:
strikes, financial crisis, receivership, creditor lawsuits,
management changes and a 13-day shutdown that blemished its long
record of uninterrupted service to the nation.
</P>
<P>
The start of the campaign to fight back and return to
profitability was signaled by the recent streamlining of the
airline's organizational structure into three major groups --
commercial, operations and finance -- to make it "lean and mean."
</P>
</TEXT>
