<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore FM on Strategic Situation in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Minister for Foreign
Affairs and Law S. Jayakumar Monday told the Parliament that there
is some basis for cautious optimism over the situation in Asia,
saying that "the fundamentals and infrastructure that made
possible three decades of growth are still there."
</P>
<P>
Giving an overview of strategic situation in Asia, Jayakumar
said, "Fortunately, the U.S.-China-Japan triangular relationship
has remained relatively stable."
</P>
<P>
"Stability in the triangular relationship will continue to
provide the basic foundation for peace and security in the
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the U.S.-China relations, Jayakumar said the first
half of 1998 saw U.S.-China relations "stabilizing to a
comfortable balance" following Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the U.S. in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton made a return visit to China in
June 1998, he noted.
</P>
<P>
But there are now signs of traditional problems resurfacing and
underlying differences have once again been brought to fore, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar stressed that "a downturn in U.S.-China relations
would not be in the interest of either party, nor of the region as
a whole".
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the U.S.-China relations can settle
on a more even keel after Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to
the U.S. in April.
</P>
<P>
On U.S.-Japan relations, Jayakumar said there was a perception
that U.S.-Japan relations suffered a slide but Clinton's visit to
Japan in November 1998 restored relations to an even keel.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that there is friction in economic and trade
relations between the U.S. and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Citing that Chinese President Jiang Zemin made an historic
state visit to Japan in November 1998, Jayakumar said China
remains high on Japan's foreign policy agenda. But he added that
it will take time for the two countries to forge a closer
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar said the economic crisis has altered the regional
strategic landscape as many economies have been affected,
triggering political changes and instability in several countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have therefore to be alert to possible instability and be
prepared for political upheaval in the region," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Jayakumar said it is in the interest of Singapore to have a
stable and peaceful balance of power in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also said Singapore welcomes a strong European engagement in
the region, saying "Europe should complement its economic
involvement in the region with a greater strategic presence."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
