<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Holds First Meeting on Women in Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Monday opened its
first national conference on women and sports in an effort to
highlight the current status of sport for women in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Women and Sports Conference 1999, with the theme "Women &AMP;
Sports: New Horizons", will focus on the barriers and mindsets
which are keeping more women and girls from taking part in sports
and exercises.
</P>
<P>
The participation rate in sports and exercise for women in
Singapore in comparison with men is low, said Ms Annabel Ess,
chairperson of the conference, in her opening address.
</P>
<P>
Only 28 percent of women in Singapore competed regularly in
sports in 1997, lagging far behind 40 percent of males, according
to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
That is not a unique Singaporean problem, but part of a
worldwide trend, said Annabel, adding that many of the barriers to
women's participation in sports in other countries were not
present in modern Singapore society.
</P>
<P>
Teo Chee Hean, Education Minister and President of the
Singapore National Olympic Council, told the conference that
Singapore women have certainly made progress in sports, both at
the national and international levels, but much can be done to
improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the role of women in positively influencing their
families towards sports.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Australia, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia,
Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam, the United States and other
countries are attending the two-day conference. 
</P>
