<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Ruling Party Accepts Election Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) hinted here Monday that
it would accept the Election Commission's decision to hold the May
general elections in two phases.
</P>
<P>
CPN-UML General Secretary Madav Kumar Nepal told a press
conference that though the decision is unconstitutional, his party
accepts it since no one has challenged it constitutionally.
</P>
<P>
The party had vehemently opposed the idea of phase-wise
election to the House of Representatives and demanded instead
election in one single day on May 3 as announced by King Birendra
when he dissolved the House on January 15.
</P>
<P>
All the other parties except the ruling Nepali Congress echoed.
But the Election Commission has decided to hold the polls in two
phases on May 3 and May 17, citing inadequate security personnel.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML also released its election manifesto at the press
conference, which calls for voting for the party to make a
majority government for political stability, good governance,
development and national pride and dignity.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto, among others, pledges further investigation into
the mysterious death of former party general secretary Madan
Bhandari.
</P>
<P>
The Mitsubishi Pajero jeep which Bhandari and another CPN-UML
leader Jeeva Raj Ashrit took fell into a river in May 1993 in
Chitwan district of central Nepal. They died but the driver
survived. The case remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto said the investigation has been left incomplete;
the process of investigation and unmasking the culprits will be
sped up.
</P>
<P>
It also pledges to take initiatives to extradite Indian armies
from Kalapani in far-western Nepal and regulate borders between
the two countries on the basis of historical and authenticated
facts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
