<HEADLINE> Myanmar Military Delegation Leaves for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A 30-strong Myanmar military
delegation, led by Commander of Triangle Region Command
Major-General Thein Sein, left here Monday for Phuket, Thailand,
to attend the 17th meeting of the two countries' Regional Border
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar delegation also includes the commanders of coastal
region and southeastern command region, state-run Radio Myanmar
reported Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to discuss the enhancement of the two
countries' cooperation in narcotic suppression, including cracking
down on drug trade and illicit trafficking in the infamous Golden
Triangle area bordering Myanmar, Thailand and Laos.
</P>
<P>
The discussion is also expected to cover issues on settlement
of border, marine and fishing disputes.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Thailand have achieved significant progress in the
fight against narcotic drugs: the arrest of amphetamine producers
and traffickers, along with destruction of more than 20 million
such tablets by Thailand in 1997-98 fiscal year; the seizure of
more than 28,000 kilos of opium and over 4,000 kilos of heroin as
well as over 26 million amphetamine tablets by Myanmar in 1988-98,
according to a joint statement issued last Tuesday at the end of
the two-day visit to Thailand by Myanmar leader Senior-General
Than Shwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
