<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Have to Live Together: Vajpayee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said Monday that since both India and Pakistan
have nuclear weapons, they have to live together to pursue peace.
</P>
<P>
In a reply to the debate in the Lower House of Parliament here
on the motion of thanks on the president's address to the joint
session of the two Houses on February 22, Vajpayee said, "We both
are now having nuclear arms with us. There is no option but to
live together. Nuclear arms are for protection and not for
attacking each other."
</P>
<P>
He said that India and Pakistan had fought three wars in the
past and a "permanent solution" had to be found to prevent
conflict. "There is no other way but to have a political
dialogue," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
While resolving pending outstanding issues, steps were being
initiated to improve trade and economic cooperation between India
and Pakistan. Besides, visa restrictions were being relaxed and
efforts were on to secure the release of captured fishermen and
return of prisoners of war by the two countries, he further said.
</P>
</TEXT>
