<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Sabah State New Chief Minister Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 15 (Xinhua) -- New chief minister Osu Sukam
of Malaysia's Sabah state was sworn in Monday to head the new
state government led by the Barisan Nasional (BN) (National
Front).
</P>
<P>
He took his oath of office before Sabah's head of state Sakaran
Dandai in Sabah's capital city of Kota Kinabalu, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Osu Sukam was sworn in as the 11th chief minister of Sabah,
East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Osu Sukam, the ruling United Malays National Organization
(UMNO) Sabah chief, was named the state's new chief minister
earlier in the day, Malaysia's Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi said at a news conference in Kota Kinabalu.
</P>
<P>
Osu, 50, took over from Bernard Dompok who was defeated in the
ninth Sabah state Legislative Assembly election held on Friday and
Saturday, to head the new BN state government which was returned
to a resounding victory in the polls.
</P>
<P>
The BN won the polls with 31 seats out of 48 seats at stake.
UMNO is the backbone of the ruling BN.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also announced that Osu would serve his term under the
rotation system introduced when the BN came to power in the state
in 1994 and would be succeeded by a leader of the Kadazandusun
community (non-Muslim) in the Sabah BN and then of the Chinese
community.
</P>
<P>
The rotation system of the chief ministership would be
continued in line with the BN concept of power sharing in the
state, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Under the rotation system for the Sabah chief minister's post,
Dompok who represented the non-Muslim Bumiputera (aboriginals)
community, was appointed the state's chief minister last year to
replace Yong Teck Lee who represented the Chinese community.
</P>
<P>
The first chief minister under the rotation system was Salleh
Tun Said who represented the Muslim bumiputera (aboriginals).
</P>
<P>
Osu's appointment marks the completion of the first round of
the rotation system and the beginning of a fresh one.
</P>
<P>
Osu was Deputy Chief Minister and Finance Minister in the
previous state government headed by Dompok.
</P>
<P>
Osu was federal Minister of Land and Cooperative Development
from 1994 to 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
