<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Sell 17.52 Million Dollars Worth of Gems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 17.52 million U.S.
dollars worth of locally produced gems, jade, pearl and jewelry
will be sold at the 36th annual Myanmar Gems Emporium due to open
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These items will be sold through competitive bidding at the
six-day state-sponsored gems emporium, said Myanmar Deputy
Minister of Mine U Myint Thein at a press briefing here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Over 300 merchants of 114 companies from 16 countries and
regions are expected to attend the emporium.
</P>
<P>
At the 35th emporium held in March last year, a total of 3.15
million U.S. dollars worth of these items were sold. The emporium
attracted 239 merchants of 161 companies from seven countries and
regions including Japan, Thailand, China and China's Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar also added a mid-year gems emporium in last
October, during which 4.29 million dollars worth of such items
were sold.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, a well-known producer of jade, ruby and sapphire in
the world, has held gems emporiums annually since 1964 with
additional mid-year ones introduced since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The country earned a total of 265 million dollars from the last
35 annual and seven mid-year gems emporiums. 
</P>
