<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Bankruptcy of GITIC (More Added) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua)-- The application by the Guangdong
International Trust and Investment Corporation (GITIC) for
bankruptcy has sent a significant message to the outside world
that the Chinese government will not repay debts for any
individual financial institutions that are not guaranteed by the
government, China's premier Zhu Rongji said at a press conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the bankruptcy of GITIC as an individual case in
the course of the financial reform in China, the premier said,
adding that "this incidence is of great significance because it
has sent a message to the world that the Chinese government will
not repay the debts for the financial institution or a financial
firm if the debts are not guaranteed by governments at various
levels in China".
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remark at a press conference which was held right
after the conclusion of the Second Session of the Ninth National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that that the foreign banks and institutions need to
make risk analysis and act prudently and cautiously in extending
loans to financial firms in China.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the approach of China in approving the bankruptcy
of GITIC is consistent with the principle of financial reform, and
also consistent with intentional practice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that "the creditor banks and financial
institutions have been too pessimistic in their estimation and
evaluation of this incident" to think that China is experiencing a
financial crisis, has no repayment capability, and is no longer
credit-worthy.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is maintaining a rapid economic growth and
has 1,46.5 billion U.S. dollars of foreign exchange reserves, and
balanced international payments.
</P>
<P>
"China is fully capable of repaying its debts, but the question
is whether the debts should be repaid by the government, the
answer is, of course, they should not," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also pointed out that even though the bankruptcy is lawful,
reasonable and fair, one should not assume that one can benefit
from the bankruptcy, and one should not rush for a bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
"I do not expect to see too many bankruptcies of financial
firms in the future, and maybe there will be none." he stressed.
</P>
<P>
But, he warned, the precondition is that the creditor banks
should not press too hard for the debt repayment beforehand or in
advance. "If you press too hard, they will have no choice but to
apply for bankruptcy," he said.
</P>
<P>
If everybody can just sit down and have a talk according to
international practice, for instance, to recapitalize the firm or
to instill fresh capital into it or to swap the debt for equity,
then the problem can be settled and there is no need to apply for
bankruptcy, Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
