<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Poland to Expand Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski said here Monday his country was satisfied with its
political relations with Malaysia but was interested in expanding
further bilateral economic and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
"Political dialogues between the two countries are proceeding
very well and Poland desires to maintain the process," he told a
press conference here after his talks with Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Poland was interested in extending and
expanding the scope of economic and trade cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Though bilateral trade expanded in recent years, there are
still "great potentials" for expansion in this field, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that based on the talks held Monday, there is goodwill
on both sides to expand bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Both sides talked about establishing direct air link between
Poland and Malaysia to the convenience of businessmen of both
sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also expressed the desire to open new fields
of cooperation such as culture, education and science and
technology as well as telecommunications, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Poland was also interested in cooperation in defense
industry between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also explored the possibility of cooperation in
third markets and Poland would promote Malaysian products in the
markets of former Soviet Union republics, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to Polish Minister of Economy Janusz
Steinhoff who was present at the press conference, bilateral trade
between Poland and Malaysia increased to 200 million U.S. dollars
in 1998 from only 9 million dollars in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski, invited by Malaysia's King Tuanku Ja'afar, arrived
here earlier Monday for a three-day state visit.
</P>
<P>
His visit is the first by a Polish head of state to Malaysia.
</P>
