<HEADLINE> India Concerned Over Japan's Levying Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- India has expressed its concern
over Japan's insistence on levying a 20 percent withholding tax on
Japanese firms importing Indian software.
</P>
<P>
Japan has breached provisions of bilateral double taxation
avoidance treaty, Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted a top
government official as saying here Monday.
</P>
<P>
At secretary level talks on bilateral economic trade between
India and Japan held in Tokyo in February this year, India had
conveyed its displeasure over Japanese insistence for charging a
20 percent withholding tax on software exported from India, said
S. Devare, secretary for economic affairs in the Ministry of
External Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side is reported to have explained that it was due
to some misunderstanding in the provisions of the bilateral double
taxation avoidance treaty.
</P>
<P>
India's software exports to Japan are expected to reach 4,000
million rupees (96.15 million U.S. dollars) in fiscal 1998-99
(April 1, 1998-March 31, 1999). It was four percent of India's
total software shipment in the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
