<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Oppose Liberalization of Farm Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 15 (Xinhua) -- World farmers oppose the
liberalization of agricultural sector in multinational trade talks
at the World Trade Organization (WTO), saying the policy benefits
only multinational companies which will sell their products more
easily.
</P>
<P>
This is a conclusion of the latest conference of the so-called
Via Campasina (World Farmers Organization), which ended here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The conference released a statement, which is available here
Monday, calling on governments throughout the world to withdraw a
proposal to liberalize the agricultural sector from the agenda of
the WTO's multinational trade talks.
</P>
<P>
It said the issue had no benefits to the majority of the world
population and was only in the interests of multinational firms
which had pressed for opening up the sector so that they could
sell their products more easily.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that opening up the farm sector would
lead to the problem of food monopoly in the world market, where
multinational companies could force farmers to produce only crops
they want.
</P>
<P>
It could also create trade wars, which, again, virtually have
no benefits to any party, especially when the world's poorest were
dying of hunger and malnutrition, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The conference, therefore, drew a conclusion that goes against
a move by the international community to open up global market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
