<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's Eastward Expansion Affects European Security Pattern (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese military experts,
commenting on the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
admitting three east European states, said here today that this
marks the first step of NATO's eastward expansion, a step that
will have a far-reaching impact on the security pattern in Europe.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they expressed doubt that "any positive
outcome could come from utilizing and enlarging this military
alliance," arguing that this step will weaken the security of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
NATO, the world's largest political and military organization,
opened its doors to Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary, the
first new members to be admitted in 17 years. The three countries
did not wait until NATO's 50th anniversary summit in Washington
next month to hand over their documents to the United States, and
have become the first former Warsaw Pact members to join NATO
after the conclusion of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Scholars studying international strategies here noted that the
actual launching of NATO's eastward expansion has altered both the
political and military map, and the political situation in Europe,
by promoting NATO as the indisputable center of the European
defense system.
</P>
<P>
Yao Youzhi, a top researcher with the Chinese Academy of
Military Sciences, said that "as an outcome of power politics,
NATO's move could invoke new confrontations." Now that the
boundary between Poland and Belarus has become a border between
NATO and the Commonwealth of Independent States, NATO's move
eastward will surly leave Russia disconcerted, as traditionally
Russia feels safe only by maintaining a buffer zone around itself.
</P>
<P>
It is also understood that NATO eventually will include such
countries as Romania and the Baltic Sea countries in its second
and third round of eastward expansion. Be it is also true that
NATO's "lengthening antennae" will undoubtedly arouse strong
opposition from Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
