<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Suggests Direct Balloting on E. Timor Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
suggested that the United Nations-sponsored direct balloting to
determine if the East Timor wants autonomy or independence should
be held in July, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"(The direct balloting could) be held in July as (revisions to
the Indonesian government's) proposal for (wide-ranging) autonomy
(in East Timor) will be completed in April," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the recent tripartite talks on East Timor,
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan tabled three options to garner
the East Timorese' view on Jakarta's proposal for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
These are that the U.N. select a number of leading East
Timorese figures who could give their views on autonomy; the U.N.
select a council comprising 35 people; and a direct vote.
</P>
<P>
On March 11, the tripartite talks, which involved Indonesia,
Portugal and the U.N., reached agreement on the third choice.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta's point of view, Alatas said, direct balloting is
much better than a referendum, which would require all East
Timorese living abroad to return home to be able to join the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said that with the use of a direct vote to determine the
true aspirations of the East Timorese, it will be proven if 90
percent of the East Timorese indeed prefer independence to
continued integration with Indonesia, as some East Timorese
pro-independence leaders claimed.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975.
It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
