<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's Eastward Expansion Affects European Security Pattern (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another scholar, Luo Yuan, said, "NATO's eastward expansion has
intensified the U.S.'s dominant role in European security, and
there are grounds for some international figures to worry about
NATO's trend toward a formidable pro-military group."
</P>
<P>
Luo also pointed out that NATO's expansionist intention is
clear to all, citing its interference in Kosovo and its recent
demand to enhance dialogues with countries in the Mediterranean
and Middle East regions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is "arranging chessmen at the most critical places on
the chessboards of the European and Asian continents" in an
attempt to "establish two strategic platforms," said Dr. Peng
Guangqian. NATO has in substance become a "tool" of the U.S. as it
seeks hegemony in Europe, he added.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the U.S. has begun to intervene militarily in other
countries, regardless of objections from the United Nations.
Backed up by the U.S., NATO began to become involved in Kosovo,
which actually runs counter to its promise to handle defence
affairs only within the scope of its member countries. NATO's
increased ability to control regional conflicts, as gained from
its eastward expansion, has supported it in adopting a daring move
in Kosovo, Peng argued.
</P>
<P>
While U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright regards
participation of the three new countries in NATO as "a continuing
process instead of a single event," the scholars here insist that
"it's needless for NATO to maintain and even to expand such a
military coalition." "It will only destroy balance and incur new
turbulence in the region," they said, calling for close attention
to NATO's expansionist trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
