<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report of IMF Suspending loan to Uganda Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has not suspended lending to Uganda but has delayed by two
months disbursement of the second tranche of the Extended
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Tumusiime Mutebile, secretary to the treasury, said
over the weekend that the 20 million U.S. dollars loan was
supposed to have been given in April and that it is likely to be
here in June now, the New Vision daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
An IMF mission was in Kampala in February to review the ESAF
program for the first half of the financial year 1998/1999 and
the multilateral financial institution decided to delay the loan
after finding Uganda had not met the nine performance criteria.
</P>
<P>
Tumusiime said Uganda missed five of the nine criteria very
marginally and the problem IMF has is with the composition of
defense expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Defense was not one of the criteria but it went up to 2.2
percent of GDP instead of 1.9 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda promised the IMF that it can guarantee defense spending
will not increase for the rest of the financial year and for all
next year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The official asserted that the IMF would release the next
tranche after monitoring Uganda's commitment over the next two
months.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's development relies heavily on loans from outside,
especially those from multilateral financial institutions like the
Work Bank and IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
