<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, U.S. Start 7th Round of Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The seventh round of
trade-agreement talks between Vietnam and the United States began
here Monday, but observers here said progress must be quickened or
a deal will remain a distant prospect.
</P>
<P>
During the current round of talks, which is expected to last
five days, the two sides will discuss a number of remaining
unresolved points, including investment services, copyright and
intellectual property, and freeing-up trade.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Dinh Luong, head of the Ministry of Trade's
Europe-America Department, is heading the Vietnamese side, while
the U.S. delegation is led by Joseph Damond.
</P>
<P>
If an agreement is not reached soon, it is quite likely that
U.S. domestic politics ahead of next year's presidential elections
could slow the process for several years, the Saigon Times daily
Monday quoted observers as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam Pete Peterson told the local press
that the two sides were working hard on the pact, so it is
possible that a deal could be sealed this year.
</P>
<P>
After the sixth round of talks in Hanoi last June, Vietnam
delivered its answers to the United States in January to some
points presented by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam earlier this month announced a one-year 50-percent
import surcharge waiver on U.S. imports starting January 1.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam last year exported to the United States about 534
million U.S. dollars worth of goods. Imports from the U.S. were
valued at some 200 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Their two-way trade reached 611 million dollars in 1997, 411
million dollars in 1995 and 597 million dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
