<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed at another all-time high Monday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries stacked on 28.2 points to close at 2,989.5
points, its highest point for the day, leaving the benchmark index
only 10.5 points away from the 3,000 point barrier.
</P>
<P>
"The market ignored the trend from Wall Street," Macquarie
Nevitts adviser Steve Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like it's heading towards the 3,000 point barrier
quickly."
</P>
<P>
Mayne said the Australian stock market had built up steam on
the back of a relatively strong reporting season for major stocks,
combined with confidence in the way the domestic economy and Asian
crisis were progressing.
</P>
<P>
The bank index surged 117.9 points, or 1.7 percent to 7,022.3
points, with three of the major players soaring more than two
percent.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia shot up 65.4 cents to 26.654
Australian dollars, Westpac bank spiked 25.1 cents to 10.892
Australian dollars and ANZ leapt 22 cents to 10.82 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank climbed 33.9 cents to 28.395 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the all industrials index gained 55 points to 5,383.3
and the all resources index firmed 4.9 points to 1,030.0 points.
</P>
<P>
Among the diversified industrials, Australia's leading company
BHP shed 11.8 cents to 12.75 Australian dollars and global miner
Rio Tinto surged 29 cents to 22.19 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Monday afternoon was
291.75 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared with a close of 293.80 U.S.
dollars an ounce on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 336.86 million stocks traded
for 585.68 million U.S. dollars. Falling stocks outnumbered rising
stocks 642 to 579 and 465 stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
