<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Expected to Spend Huge Sum on Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia is expected to spend 5
billion Australian dollars (3.15 billion U.S. dollars) to replace
the Royal Australian Air Force's aging F/A-18 Hornet fighters and
F-111 bombers in what will be Australia's biggest purchase of new
defense equipment.
</P>
<P>
A government discussion paper on options for fast jet
replacement, set to be released in the next few months, will
canvass the expected awesome cost of maintaining a front-line
fighter and strike capability.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected to assess what level of air force
capability is needed in line with current strategic assessments
and whether the job needs one or two types of aircraft, the
Australian Associated Press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper will be a first for an Australian government in
promoting public debate on what will be a major outlay of
taxpayers' funds.
</P>
<P>
Under current expectations, the Hornets will reach the end of
their useful life in the second decade of the next century and the
F-111s a few years later. That would make the oldest Hornet around
30 and the oldest F-111 a geriatric 50.
</P>
<P>
With the conclusion of the Hornet fatigue test program now
being conducted by the Defense Science and Technology Organization
in Melbourne, the air force should have a clear indication of just
how long it can keep the aircraft flying before they start to
break.
</P>
<P>
Both the Hornets and F-111s are regarded as superior to any
aircraft flown by any regional air force, the F-111s by a big
margin indeed.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Australian Air Force initially ordered 75 Hornets in
1981 but has since lost a few in accidents.
</P>
<P>
An order for 24 F-111s was placed in 1963 with the first
delivered to Australia in December 1973. In 1993 the air force
bought another 15 used aircraft from the U.S. Air Force for spares
and making up attrition losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
