<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Constitutional Amendments Propel China's Reform and Opening-up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After 10 years of rapid development, the private sector now
contributes some 15 percent of China's gross domestic product (GDP)
, while shareholding and overseas-funded enterprises also become
an important part of the national economy, said Yu.
</P>
<P>
The second Constitutional amendment in 1993 abolished the
central planning economy long practiced in China and decided that
the country would strive to build a "socialist market economy".
</P>
<P>
"This amendment helped China to go on a fast track of economic
growth and brought enormous changes to the country's economic
system," noted Yu.
</P>
<P>
At present, there is an abundant supply of all kinds of
commodities in China, while prices of 97.3 percent of these
commodities are decided by market demands.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jiafu, a legal expert with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that the fundamental purpose of the current
Constitutional amendment is to safeguard the cause of reform and
opening-up, add impetus to the development of China's productive
forces and further improve the people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
Private businessmen and entrepreneurs across China have warmly
welcomed this amendment, which not only stipulates that the
country should adhere to a fundamental economic system under which
the public ownership dominates and other forms of ownership are
allowed to co-exist and seek common development, but also bolsters
the status of the private sector as "an important component" of
the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
"Many private enterprises used to prefer short-term investment
for worries about possible policy changes," said Liu Yonghao, a
Chinese private businessman ranked among the world's 500 richest
persons by Forbes magazine. "Now we feel safe to make long-term
investment and plan for development in the long run."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Constitutional Amendments Propel China's Reform and Opening-up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A Constitutional amendment draft
adopted by China's top lawmaking body, the National People's
Congress (NPC), here today has enshrined Deng Xiaoping Theory,
which has guided China's reform and opening-up drive in the past
two decades, into the country's Constitution, thus providing a
legal guarantee for the reforms and opening-up at the top level.
</P>
<P>
Theorists and law experts here describe the amendment this time,
the third of its kind since 1988, as "a milestone."
</P>
<P>
"It also shows the strong determination of the collective
leadership of the third generation of the ruling Communist Party
of China (CPC) with Jiang Zemin at the core and the entire Chinese
people to forge ahead along the line of reform and opening-up
initiated by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping," commented a
Party theorist who attended the just-concluded Second Session of
the Ninth NPC as a deputy.
</P>
<P>
According to Pang Xianzhi, director of the Party Literature
Research Center of the CPC Central Committee, China's three
amendments to its Constitution, which was enacted in 1982, are
actually efforts to raise all successful experience of reform and
opening-up to the level of the will of the state and the people.
</P>
<P>
"China's reform actually started with the reform of its
ownership system, which occurred first in the rural areas and then
in the cities," said economist Yu Zuyao.
</P>
<P>
There were already some 220,000 private enterprises and more
than 10 million private business people in China when the first
Constitutional amendment was made in 1988, which allowed the
private sector to exist and develop as a "supplement" to the
formerly "extremely pure" public ownership economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Constitutional Amendments Propel China's Reform and Opening-up (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Law experts and sociologists also praised the current amendment
for endorsing the principle of "governing the country according to
law" and including the wording that China will remain in the
primary stage of socialism "for a long period of time."
</P>
<P>
Enshrining the principle of "governing the country according to
law" into the Constitution shows that China has bid a complete
farewell to the rule by man and will adopt the rule of law, which
can help prevent the recurrence of any internal disorder such as
the "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976), said Wang Jiafu.
</P>
<P>
The concept that the primary stage of socialism will remain "
for a long period of time" will help people to always keep a sober
mind and help the cause of reform and opening-up to avoid any
unnecessary setbacks," said sociologist Lu Xueyi.
</P>
<P>
While China probably only needs several dozens of years to
accomplish its transition from a planned economy to a market
economy, Lu said, it might take more than one hundred years for
the country to develop from a traditional agricultural society
into a modern industrial society.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Zheng, an official with the NPC Standing
Committee, legislators attending this year's NPC session have
submitted a number of bills concerning legislation efforts related
to the Constitutional amendment, such as enacting a law on private
businesses and law on individual bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
"Some of these proposed motions, such as a law on property
rights, are of critical importance to the further development of
reform and opening-up, and the NPC Standing Committee has included
them in its legislative agenda," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0160 </DOCNO>
