<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks on Kosovo Resume in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The delegates of the two conflicting sides of Kosovo are
expected to sign a peace agreement on Kosovo which was presented
by the six-nation Contact Group on former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
No deadline was given for them to accept the peace plan, but
the European Unions officials have expected the talks to end in
from four days to one week.
</P>
<P>
At stake are two most sensitive issues -- the deployment of a
NATO-led international peacekeeping force in Kosovo, and the
abandoning by Kosovo Albanians the request for independence and
the disarmament of the Albanian separatist force the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav government has categorically rejected the
perspective of the deployment of a foreign force in Kosovo,
considering such a move as one of occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian side has also refused to give up its call for
independence after a three-year interim period and the disarmament
of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
Western mediators gave a more prudent tone this time than
during the Rambouillet talks three weeks ago as for the chances of
a success of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Just like at the Rambouillet talks, the Serb delegation was
headed by the vice prime minister of the Serbian Republic, Ratko
Markovic, but was accompanied by the President of the Serbian
Republic Milan Milutinovic who is not a member of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
The two co-chairmen of the talks, French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine and British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, will have
a meeting with the three international mediators for Kosovo Monday
afternoon, said French foreign ministry sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
