<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly All Filipino Children Suffer Dental Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-eight percent of Filipino
children have rotten teeth or suffer from tooth decay, the Health
Department said in a report issued at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
This dental disease is one of the five leading causes of
morbidity in the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the past, there had been poor appreciation of the important
role of oral health in the improvement of the quality of life and
in the socio-economic development of the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Except for the elite and affluent, Filipinos continue to live
with their dental problems in ignorance or with acceptance,
resigned suffering for lack of access to information and basic
dental services.
</P>
<P>
Besides esthetic and psychological effects, this disease
contributes to the high frequency rates of absenteeism in school
and industry.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department is sponsoring a program to urge citizens
to donate kiddie tooth brushes and support dental health education
activities in schools and communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
