<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Further Open Foreign Exchange Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The officials said a team of five experts under the supervision
of the bank governor Daudi Balali is undertaking the task which is
envisaged to be completed before the end of this financial year by
June 30.
</P>
<P>
When new laws and regulations are in place, it is expected that
any person can bring in and repatriate foreign currency abroad
without a requirement to buy or invest in the country first.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994, transactions at Tanzania's foreign exchange
market has been moving away from foreign exchange controls to
increasingly market-oriented.
</P>
<P>
However, the current regulations require one to either buy or
make investment in the country before the person is permitted to
repatriate foreign currency abroad.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts see the new move as further signs of
Tanzania's commitment to the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund to make the country more attractive to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the BoT officials refuted that there are plans to
soften the current tight fiscal policies on grounds that poor
liquidity is affecting import business.
</P>
<P>
The current BoT goal is to further keep down inflation rate
which now stands at 9.1 percent and strengthen the Tanzania
shilling, they observed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
