<HEADLINE> Uganda to Send Back Choppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
decided to send back the two MT 24 helicopter gun ships to the
manufacturer because they were not overhauled before selling as
required by the purchase contract.
</P>
<P>
Monday's New Vision paper quoted top military sources as saying
Sunday that the military had rejected the un overhauled choppers
and the army would not ply them before this controversy was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that they have given the supplier, the British
Virgin Island registered company Consolidated Sales Corporation
(CSC), three weeks to meet the conditions or lose the contract
and refund the original cost plus the services lost so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, the supplier should rectify and
defect in the helicopters and if it fails, the contract provides
for arbitration, the sources said .
</P>
<P>
A Ugandan technical team will go and have a look at the
facility where the choppers are supposed to the overhauled, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters, at a lost of 1.5 million U.S. dollars each,
was supplied from Belarus, a former Soviet Union republic, early
last year.
</P>
<P>
They are part of the four combat/transport aircraft to be
supplied by CSC, The purchase agreement was signed in February
1997. 
