<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Rejects Lab-theft Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese ambassador to the
United States Li Zhaoxing Sunday refuted allegations by some
American newspapers about Chinese stealing of U.S. nuclear secrets
as "completely unfounded" and "extremely irresponsible."
</P>
<P>
China has always strictly abided by the norms of international
law, committed itself to cooperation accords with other countries,
respected their domestic laws, and has never carried out illegal
activities abroad, Li said in an interview with Xinhua, People's
Daily and Chinese Central Television.
</P>
<P>
Some newspapers here alleged that by the end of the 70s, a
Taiwan-born American scientist at a laboratory in California
leaked to China neutron-bomb secrets, and in the middle of the 80s,
some people again provided China with warhead secrets so that
China could produce weapons of a similar kind.
</P>
<P>
"These are sheer fabrications," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The work at the laboratory in California sensationally
described by some American reporters was, in fact, concerned only
with topics of international scientific conferences and contents
of normal academic exchanges, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li also retorted the rumored leakage of U.S. laser technology
to China. "In a statement published in February 1998, seven
Chinese scientists refuted the allegation by providing lots of
convincing evidences. But not an American newspaper has so far had
the courage to publish the statement, nor has any American
reporter responded to it," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the 90s, Li said, laboratories of the two countries carried
out some exchange and cooperative programs at the request of the U.
S. side and "in accordance with the principles of equality and
mutual benefit, openness and transparency."
</P>
<P>
Such exchange programs, which exist among many countries in the
world, tally with U.S. interests and have nothing to do with the
so-called "lab-theft", Li said. "I'm glad to see that many
Americans have recently spoken out from a sense of justice,
pointing out that the fabrications were made out of ulterior
political motives," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, many scientists and engineers in China had
written to him, expressing indignation over the irresponsible U.S.
press reports, which they regarded as an insult to Chinese
scientists and as a sign of arrogance and prejudice of the rumor-
mongers.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists are capable and intelligent enough to
develop China's own high-technology, and they are willing to
conduct exchanges with foreign counterparts and learn from each
other, li said. But, he stressed, "this can only be done on the
basis of mutual respect."
</P>
<P>
Li said that it is no surprise that rumors and slanders have
occurred from time to time recently, since there are always some
Americans who do not want to see any progress in Sino-U.S.
relations.
</P>
<P>
Sino-American ties have been moving forward following the
exchange of visits by the heads of state of the two countries, but
those people felt uneasy and started to make troubles. They played
up "China threat," trying to stymie normal scientific and
technological exchanges and cooperation and undermine the sound
development of the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li said the perverse acts of those people who refuse to accept
hard facts, and disregard the common interests and aspirations of
the Chinese and American peoples will yield no benefits.
</P>
<P>
The veteran diplomat said that the Chinese people treasure the
friendly ties between China and the United States. The upcoming
visit of Premier Zhu Rongji to the United States at the invitation
of President Clinton represents another major event in Sino-U.S.
relations. His visit has been welcomed in the United States and
this is the mainstream in American society.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to joint hands with the U.S. side to make
preparations and overcome obstacles so as to ensure the visit a
complete success," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Foreign Trade Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The import and export volume of
Shanghai, China's economic powerhouse, reached 3.9 billion U.S.
dollars in the first two months this year, up 18.3 percent from
the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The city's contracted foreign investment totaled 752 million
dollars, an increase of 42.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Office reported Shanghai's export volume at 2.2
billion dollars and import volume at 1.69 billion dollars, up 31.8
percent and 4.4 percent, respectively, from the same two months
last year.
</P>
<P>
The export volume of overseas-funded enterprises reached 1.38
billion dollars in the January-February period, accounting for 61.
3 percent of the city's total, compared with 50.1 percent in the
same 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
The operations of several large overseas-funded enterprises
engaged in the processing industry contributed to the rapid growth
of the city's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
For example, exports of one factory set up by the U.S. computer-
memory chip corporation Intel, in the Pudong New Area last year,
climbed to 61.59 million dollars in the first two months this year,
compared with 17.8 million dollars in the same 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the export volume of state-owned enterprises which
were hit by the Asian financial crisis last year also recovered.
In one instance, the Baoshan Iron and Steel Company witnessed an
export growth rate of 38.5 percent in the first two months this
year.
</P>
<P>
However, the export volume of foreign trade companies dropped
by 2.2 percent, and their newly signed contracted export volume
declined to 1.36 billion dollars, a drop of 18 percent compared
with 1998.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that industrial projects make up 54
percent of the 233 overseas-funded enterprises approved in the
January-February period, and the number of projects involving
investments of over 10 million dollars each reached 24, an
increase of 26.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the city's import and export volume stood at 31.34
billion dollars, and its contracted foreign investment totaled 5.
85 billion dollars, accounting for about 10 percent of the country'
s total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
