<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Readers Form China's Largest Book Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China's rural area has become the
country's largest book market, according to a monthly publication
released today by the Information Center of the Press and
Publications Administration.
</P>
<P>
The publication, the New Book Catalogue of China, said that the
number of rural readers has been rapidly increasing during the
past two decades of reform and opening, and that the book
consumption growth rate of China's rural residents now exceeds
that of urban residents.
</P>
<P>
At the recently concluded '99 Beijing Book Fair, books on
agriculture, and farmers and rural life were among the most
popular. More than 30,000 sets of a 160-volume series, the
Achieving Prosperity Book Series For the 900 Million Chinese
Farmers, were sold at the book fair.
</P>
<P>
"The Third Plenary Session of the 15th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, held late last year, emphasized the
fundamental status of agriculture and decided to further enhance
the rural work, thus creating a good environment for the booming
rural book market," said Zhang Lianping, a senior publisher in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Further exploring the rural book market should be a key goal
for China's publishers in the next several years," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, books related to culture and education,
agricultural technology, life practices, and social sciences are
the ones most welcomed by China's rural readers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
