<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silt-Discharge Tunnels for Xiaolangdi Project Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Three silt-discharge tunnels
for the World Bank-financed Xiaolangdi water control project on
the Yellow River have been completed ahead of schedule, creating
favorable conditions for the project to pass this year's flood
season safely.
</P>
<P>
Considered the greatest project yet for harnessing the Yellow
River, China's second longest, the Xiaolangdi project consists of
underground power-generating units, flood- and silt-discharge
tunnels and networks, and a dam. It is expected to be completed
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
By then, the project, in conjunction with the Sanmenxia, Luhun
and Guxian reservoirs and embankments downstream, will be able to
withstand even the worst floods.
</P>
<P>
The three silt-discharge tunnels, each 1,105 meters long and 6.
5 meters in diameter, have been built within the mountains on the
northern bank of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Engineers with the Xiaolangdi project said that the newly
completed silt-discharge tunnels will be used together with two
other water diversion tunnels to discharge water during this year'
s flood season, which usually occurs in the summer.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi project, including the dam which is 1,667 meters
long and 154 meters high, is being constructed at a cost of 34.75
billion yuan, including World-Bank loans totaling 1.1 billion U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Rejects Israeli Plan to Reduce Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has rejected an Israeli plan
to reduce its water supplies to the kingdom by 60 percent in 1999,
the semiofficial Jordan Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a dragging drought in the Jewish state, Israel proposed
a 60 percent cut in its annual water supplies to Jordan promised
under the 1994 Israel-Jordan peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was rejected by a Jordanian delegation during a
bilateral meeting in Jerusalem on Sunday, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan wants to make it clear that the peace accord has set up
our legitimate water shares, and it has nothing to do with a
drought in Israel," Jordan Times quoted an unnamed official in the
Jordanian delegation as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace treaty, Israel extracts 12 million cubic
meters of water from the Yarmouk River from May 15 to October 15
annually, and Jordan gets the rest of the river's flow.
</P>
<P>
From October 16 to May 14, Israel pumps out 13 million cubic
meters of water from the Yarmouk river, and Jordan allows Israel
to pump an additional 20 million cubic meters from the river.
</P>
<P>
In return for the additional water, Israel promised to
transfer 20 million cubic meters of water to Jordan through the
Jordan River in summer time.
</P>
<P>
Israel assured Jordan last December that it would comply with
the water clauses in the peace treaty, refuting statements by its
Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan that it would reconsider the
water supplies to Jordan in 1999 due to the drought.
</P>
<P>
His remarks prompted Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon to
send an official clarification to Amman, saying Israel would stand
by all its commitments in the peace treaty, including water.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Sabah State New Chief Minister Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Osu Sukam, the ruling United
Malays National Organization (UMNO) Sabah chief, was Monday named
the new chief minister of the Sabah state, East Malaysia, it was
officially announced.
</P>
<P>
Osu, 50, takes over from Bernard Dompok who was defeated in the
state polls held on Friday and Saturday, to head the freshly
returned government of the Barisan Nasional (BN) (National Front)
of which UMNO is the backbone.
</P>
<P>
The BN won the ninth Sabah Legislative Assembly election with
31 seats out of 48 seats at stake.
</P>
<P>
Osu's appointment was announced by Malaysia's Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi at a news conference in Sabah's
capital city of Kota Kinabalu, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Osu is scheduled to take his oath of office before Sabah Sultan
Sakaran Dandai later in the day, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the decision on Osu's appointment was conveyed to
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is BN chairman and concurred
with the decision.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also announced that Osu would serve his term under the
rotation system and would be succeeded by a leader of the
Kadazandusun community in the Sabah BN and then from the Chinese
community.
</P>
<P>
The rotation system of the chief ministership would be
continued in line with the BN concept of power sharing in the
state, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Osu will be Sabah's 11th chief minister and also the sixth in
the last five years alone since the rotation system was introduced
after the BN came to power in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Osu's appointment marks the completion of the first round of
the rotation system and the beginning of a fresh one.
</P>
<P>
Osu was Deputy Chief Minister and Finance Minister in the
previous state government headed by Dompok.
</P>
<P>
Osu was federal Minister of Land and Cooperative Development
from 1994 to 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
