<HEADLINE> Turkish President Calls for Pressure on Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel called again for international pressure on Greece to stop
what Ankara terms Greece's support for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Daily News published on here Monday,
Demirel said he expects the "civilized world" to pressure Athens
into abiding by its treaty obligations and stop supporting
terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if Greece continues its behavior, there will be
sanctions that Turkey would take, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Greece of aiding the outlawed Kurdish
Workers Party (PKK), a charged denied by Athens.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two long-time foes worsened after the
capture of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan last month. Ocalan was
kidnaped by Turkish commandos when he was leaving the residence of
Greek Ambassador to Nairobi, Kenya, where he had taken shelter for
12 days.
</P>
<P>
Turkey held Ocalan, now jailed in a prison on Imrali Island in
Marmara Sea near western Turkey, responsible for leading the PKK
in launching a 15-year-old guerrilla war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over
37,000 lives since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
