<HEADLINE> Brazilian Soccer Team Captain to Make Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Rai, captain of the 1994
World Cup champions Brazilian side, will make a comeback next
month from a seven-month injury layoff, it was reported here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old midfielder, who pulled his left knee ligament
in a national championship match last August, has resumed practice
recently and plans to return to action for his club Sao Paulo in
April.
</P>
<P>
"I will be as good as the lads, though now I'm a grandfather,"
Rai, whose daughter gave birth to a baby boy last year, told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
But he quickly ruled out any hopes of being selected to the
national squad.
</P>
<P>
"I had my good old days. But now it's time for Ronaldo and
Rivaldo," said Rai, who made his last appearance in the famous
golden shirt just before the 1998 World Cup finals. But he was
eventually dropped out by the then Brazilian coach Mario Zagallo.
</P>
<P>
Rai, whose contract with Sao Paulo expires next year, said
after that he wants to get a try at the English soccer before
quitting the game for good.
</P>
<P>
He will then concentrate on a the Youth Soccer Fund, which he
set up jointly with his once-time national teammate, AC Milan
midfielder Leonardo. 
</P>
