<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Trends for Chinese Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
drafting measures aimed at accelerating economic growth by
increasing consumer spending this year.
</P>
<P>
According to an article in the latest issue of Outlook, a major
weekly magazine in China, China formerly relied on investment to
achieve economic growth. Now, however, the country hopes to
stimulate economic growth by expanding both investment and
consumption, the so-called "two wheels" which will support
economic increase this year.
</P>
<P>
China recently abolished several outdated measures on
consumption restrictions, and lowered both the cost of electricity
in rural areas and telecommunications service fees.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will focus its attention on improving
the quality of economic growth rather than simply economic growth-
rate figures, as a result of several defective infrastructure
projects brought to light last year.
</P>
<P>
China increased investment in infrastructure projects by 100
billion yuan last year in order to realize the goal of maintaining
an eight percent economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses will also have more room for development
this year, as they are now constitutionally a component of China's
economy, and the private economy is expected to become a strong
driving force behind economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
