<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Electricity Export Decreases Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's electricity exports
decreased last year with the value of export for January to
September amounting to 3.6 million U.S. dollars, as compared with
11.9 million dollars for the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 Economic Report by the country's finance ministry
attributed this fall mainly to the import reduction by neighboring
Zimbabwe, which imports over 80 percent of Zambia's electricity
exports.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Zambia also said in its latest annual report that
increased electricity production in the importing countries,
Zimbabwe in particular, led to their reduction in importation of
Zambia's electricity.
</P>
<P>
The report said electricity generation from January to November
of last year fell by 4.7 percent and stood at less than seven
million MWH in 1998 compared with over seven million MWH in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The fall in electricity generation was due to the significant
decline in the electricity exports and sluggish demand by the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)," the report said.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM's electricity consumption dropped as its production was
reduced. ZCCM is still in process of privatization and needs huge
capital investment.
</P>
<P>
The electrictiy generation at the main hydro-power stations
fell by 4.6 percent in the period under review, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Targets 6.4 Percent GDP Growth Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's national budget for
the 1999-2000 fiscal year is being prepared with an ambitious
target of achieving a 6.4-percent growth in the gross domestic
product (GDP), the Bangladesh Observer daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The expected growth is significantly higher than the estimated
3.8 percent growth for the current fiscal year ending June 30, the
daily said.
</P>
<P>
The budget will pursue an action plan to achieve the targeted
GDP growth by the year 2000, the newspaper quoted Finance Ministry
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The action plan is aimed at intensifying the government's
efforts to dispel policy uncertainty, instill business confidence
and strengthen macro-economic management, they said.
</P>
<P>
Like previous years, the budget for the 1999-2000 fiscal year
will give priority to reducing fiscal deficit by improving tax
collection, controlling current expenditure and terminating
less-important development projects from the Annual Development
Program (ADP).
</P>
<P>
The budget is also likely to provide some special incentives to
increase export earnings and accelerate industrialization.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings during the next fiscal year are expected to be
around 6.3 billion U.S. dollars, 9.4 percent higher than that of
the current fiscal year's estimated 5.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector as a whole is projected to grow by 8.7
percent, mainly due to a pickup in the large-scale manufacturing
sector, which was growing by 5 percent during the current fiscal
year and is expected to expand by 10 percent in the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector, mostly affected by last year's
devastating floods, will be given priority in the Annual
Development Plan, and annual growth in the sector is expected to
be 8.7 percent by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
