<HEADLINE> Dissatisfied Consumers Receive Free Legal Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The principals in ten major
consumer disputes are receiving free legal assistance in the
ongoing fight to protect their rights.
</P>
<P>
This assistance is being arranged by the Legal Affairs
Department and the Management Committee of the Jianhao Legal
Assistance Fund of the China Consumers News.
</P>
<P>
Among the beneficiaries are 200 elderly consumers who filed a
complaint against the China Martial Arts Association (CMAA).
</P>
<P>
They were among the l0,000 elderly who were asked to pay 40
yuan (about 5 U.S. dollars) for outfits to be worn during a
Taijiquan competition at Tiananmen Square last October. The
dispute arose from the poor quality of the clothing.
</P>
<P>
Another case involves a consumer in the city of Zhumadian in
Henan Province who spent 3,500 yuan to buy a pair of Swiss Titoni
brand watches which later were verified by a quality supervision
center in Beijing to be counterfeit products. The consumer then
filed a complaint against the department store that sold him the
watches.
</P>
<P>
Other cases concern an irresponsible travel agency, poor-
quality seed strains, cheating in the sales of mail-order
commodities, and delays in the transport of goods. 
</P>
