<HEADLINE> Kenyan Banks to Sack Hundreds of Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Three of Kenya's four major
commercial banks are to lay off hundreds of employees in new
cost-cutting measures aimed at enhancing profits, a leading
regional newspaper The East African reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank has revealed it would shed about 700 out of its
3,400 employees. The year-long reduction has just started and the
first 340 employees are expected to leave by June 30.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Commercial Bank and the National Bank are to make similar
 announcements this week. The boards of the two banks were said to
have held emergency meetings over the past two weeks and are
scheduled to hold further meetings before announcing their lay-off
plans.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Commercial Bank is expected to retrench its staff by 800
from 4,200 and the National Bank of Kenya is planning to cut
between 350 and 400 of its 1,350-strong staff.
</P>
<P>
The drastic reductions by the three banks will affect all
categories of staff, from management to low-level employees.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank of Kenya estimates that the banking sector holds
about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in bad debts, which requires
commercial banks to take measures to regain credibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
