<HEADLINE> 80,000 Israeli Civil Servants on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Some 80,000 Israeli civil
servants started their strike Monday morning after the Labor
Federation and the Treasury failed on Sunday to solve the wage
disputes.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strike, outpatient clinics in government hospitals
were closed, the Interior Ministry stopped to issue passports and
identity cards, the Customs Authority refused to release goods
waiting in the ports, and neither the courts nor the National
Insurance Institutes receive the public.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how long the strike will last, but the Civil
Service Commissioner Shmuel Hollander has told heads of government
offices that employees who do not work will not be paid.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the civil servants' stoppage, nearly 400,000
other public sector employees have threatened an open-ended strike
at the beginning of next week to protest the government's
opposition to wage increases, said the Labor Federation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Finance Ministry on Sunday said it is
preparing for a long and difficult strike, given the Labor
Federation's excessive demands in public sector collective
bargaining talks.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Meir Sheetrit has agreed that the public
sector wages be adjusted for inflation, translating into a 3.8
percent rise, far below the Labor Federation demanded.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry's deputy spokesman Aviram Cohen said
Sunday that Sheetrit had given his assurance to protect worker's
salaries, but refuses to cave in to the outrageous Federation
demand for 16 percent wage hike.
</P>
<P>
Each percent is some 200 million U.S. dollars and if the
Finance Ministry gives in to their demands, it will lead to the
collapse of the entire economy.
</P>
<P>
Salary has become a major problem for the government.
Employees at the Defense Ministry started their strike last week
for wage increase, while workers of Israel's largeest telephone
company Bezeq walked out of their work beginning Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
