<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People in Xinjiang Shake off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
region in northwest China brought 300,000 more rural residents out
of poverty last year thanks to economic development and increased
grain output.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the average net per capita income of farmers in 30
poverty-stricken counties reached 1,000 yuan, 100 yuan more than
in 1997, and the region's poverty rate declined from 17 percent in
1995 to 6 percent in 1998, according to the autonomous region's
poverty-relief department.
</P>
<P>
But Xinjiang still has 500,000 people living below the poverty
line, with an average net per capita income of less than 670 yuan
a year.
</P>
<P>
Most of these people live in the southern part of the region,
including Hotan, Kizil, and Kashi, and the pastoral areas in the
northern part. Their poverty is caused mainly by a weak economy,
poor access to transport, and harsh natural conditions.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the central government paid special
attention to the work of poverty-relief in the far northwest
region of the country, and listed aid-the-poor projects as part of
China's efforts to narrow the gap between the eastern and western
parts of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The central government invested a record 970 million yuan last
year in poverty-relief work, with local government supporting
funds amounting to 200 million yuan. About 90 percent of this
money was spent to build water and electricity projects, roads,
and other infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
As a result, roads in the 30 poverty-stricken counties were
increased by 2,000 kilometers,, and most of the villages now have
access to electricity and telecommunications. The drinking-water
problem was also solved.
</P>
<P>
In addition, taxes were either reduced or exempted for poor
people, made possible by an autonomous regional government subsidy
of 15 million yuan last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Teach Local Tongues at Varsity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Three tribal Kenyan languages,
namely Kikuyu, Dholuo and Luhya, are to be taught at Nairobi
University from the next academic year, a linguistics professor
has said.
</P>
<P>
G.M. Nyombe, Chairman of the Linguistics and African Languages
Department at the university, said the courses have been
introduced in response to the country's current financial,
academic and cultural needs, the weekly East African reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the three languages was based on the results
of the 1989 population census, which listed the Kikuyu, Luhya and
Luo as the largest ethnic communities.
</P>
<P>
At present, the only African language taught at the university
in Kenya is Kiswahili. It is taught together with English in the
formal education programs.
</P>
<P>
Nyombe noted that "the suppression of local languages has
forced Africans to remain intellectually dependent on foreign
scientific and cultural prescriptions because local languages are
assumed not to be developed enough to meet the country's needs."
</P>
<P>
The professor said the language center of his department would
start with a service unit, which should be operational in August,
with its initial objective to provide services to individuals and
groups.
</P>
<P>
One of the language center's first tasks, he added, is to
translate the Kenya's constitution and laws into Kiswahili and the
three ethnic languages from the existing linguistic
characteristics of a given language. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
