<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 07:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elections Only Solution to Afghan Issue: Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- An leading Iranian newspaper on
Monday called for "free and fair elections" to be held in
Afghanistan in order to put an end to the country's
two-decade-long bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary on Sunday's landmark agreement reached between
Afghan warring factions, Tehran Times said that "such a
breakthrough, although a positive step in itself, cannot lead to
a durable peace in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia who control over 90 percent of the country
and the opposition Northern Alliance led by President Burhanuddin
Rabbani, on Sunday agreed on a joint government, exchange of
prisoners of war and continuation of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Tehran Times, believed to close to the Foreign
Ministry, regretted that neither the Northern Alliance nor the
Taliban have ever tried to hold nationwide elections in that
country to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It noted that only free and fair elections under U.N.
supervision will pave the way for the Afghan people to shape a
broad-based government based on national will and harmony.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Pakistan, two big neighbors, welcomed the Afghan
factions' accord reached in Ashkhabad, Turkmenistan under the
auspices of the U.N.. They hoped it would pave the way for
restoration of peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said on
Sunday that Iran welcomes the agreements to continue talks in
order to bring about a lasting peace through the formation of a
broad-based government, composed of all Afghan ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that war and bloodshed would be halted in
Afghanistan through establishment of a cease-fire and further
talks involved all Afghan parties, tribes and ethnic groups would
prepare the ground for formation of a popular, independent and
non-aligned government in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 800 Congolese Soldiers Flee Into Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 800 armed Congolese
soldiers running away from a rebel offensive in Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) have fled into Zambia through Kaputa in
Northern Province in the last few days, Times of Zambia newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper, quoted Kaputa District Council senior administrative
official Evaristo Kafwembela and Parliament Member Samuel Mukupa,
as saying that another 10,000 civilians including some French
settlers who escaped from the war have also crossed into Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Kafwembela, who had just arrived from Kaputa, told the paper
Sunday that 800 plus soldiers who entered Zambia through the
Muchenja border post about 15 kilometers from Kaputa surrendered
themselves to Zambian authorities and voluntarily handed over
their weapons.
</P>
<P>
They are camped at the Minestone shed where the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Zambia Army and other aid
agencies have put up temporary structures for shelter.
</P>
<P>
Mukupa, who expressed worries that the armed soldiers coming
into Zambia are too many, has called for serious action by the
government.
</P>
<P>
He also worried that the large number of foreigners coming in
could compound the problem in Kaputa, a cholera infested area.
</P>
<P>
"We have had refugees coming in for a long time, but this
figure, 10,000 plus, is an all time high. We may not be competent
enough to handle the situation especially that there are armed
people involved, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation is so bad that some French settlers running away
from the war are now in Zambia with all their belongings including
farm animals, he said.
</P>
<P>
More Zambian defense personnel in the region are being
mobilized to go to the area, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
