<HEADLINE> Philippoussis Beats Moya to Win Champions Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Spain's Carlos Moya may be the
new No. 1 player in the world, but Australia's Mark Philippoussis
was the top player on the court Sunday in California.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis utilized his biggest weapon serve to wear down
the fourth-seeded Moya in the final set and post a 5-7, 6-4, 6-4,
4-6, 6-2 victory in the day's five-set final of the 2.2 million U.
S. dollars Champions Cup ATP tournament in Indian Wells.
</P>
<P>
The Australian broke Moya twice in the final set before
sealing his first Super 9 title in just under three hours with his
23rd ace on match point.
</P>
<P>
"It feels great," Philippoussis said. "It's extra special
knowing that Carlos was No. 1 in the world. I played some great
tennis today. I was just very pleased."
</P>
<P>
By reaching the final here, Moya will take the world's top
spot over from American Pete Sampras when the new ATP rankings are
released on Monday. However, his lead over Sampras will be only
37 points. The Spaniard would have held a 190-point lead over
Sampras with a victory on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Philippoussis improved to a career-best 14-2
this season and will move from No. 16 to the 11th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
