<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lankan President Orders Probe of Journalist Assault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has ordered a full scale three-pronged inquiry into
the incident which led to the abduction and assault of a local
journalist, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said the three-tiered inquiry will comprise independent
inquiries from the army, the police and a special investigation by
the Criminal Investigation Department.
</P>
<P>
Srilal Priyantha of the independent Sinhalese language
newspaper, the Lakbima (Motherland), was abducted from his
boarding house, brutally assaulted and tied to a tree in the early
hours of Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
A gang of ten unidentified thugs visited Priyantha's lodgings
at Nugegoda in the suburbs of Colombo, blindfolded him and took
him away in a vehicle to Kalubowila, about five miles away.
</P>
<P>
There, in a deserted block of land they had assaulted him,
placed him in two jute bags and tied him to a tree. Neighbors had
later come to his rescue and taken him to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Political and Defense analysts along with the national media
attribute this to be an act of individuals who have resented a
series of investigative reports which the journalist had written
in his weekly column.
</P>
<P>
In his column titled "Allas saha Dooshana" (Bribery and
Corruption), he had highlighted a series of corrupt practices in
the armed forces and the police department and also in a number of
government departments and corporations.
</P>
<P>
The paper had also on Sunday carried an exposure by him of how
an army brigadier had led a military terror gang to mercilessly
assault a woman and abduct her husband. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
