<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rodman Takes Leave of Absense from LA Lakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Los Angeles Lakers forward
Dennis Rodman did not accompany the team for Sunday's game against
the Sacramento Kings and has taken an indefinite leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
Lakers spokesman John Black said that the flamboyant Rodman,
who has helped the Lakers extend their winning streak to 10 games,
left the team for unspecified personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Dennis asked for and has been granted a leave of absence,"
Black said Sunday morning. "That is all that has been determined
at this time."
</P>
<P>
Black said it was uncertain when Rodman would return to the
Lakers, who open a six-game, nine-day road trip this evening.
</P>
<P>
When the Lakers signed Rodman last month, they knew they were
acquiring a player who keeps management on its toes with his
unpredictable mood swings and disdain for rules. As a result, the
Lakers initally are downplaying the latest development.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to freak out about it," coach Kurt Rambis said.
"It's just something we're going to have to deal with."
</P>
<P>
Rodman did not practice Saturday, his second missed practice
in a week, but did meet briefly with Rambis, Black said.
</P>
<P>
The seven-time NBA rebounding champion signed with the Lakers
on February 23 and has averaged 10.3 rebounds in nine games. He
sat out the second half of Friday's win over the Golden State
Warroirs because of a score elbow.
</P>
<P>
The latest development continues a turbulent season for the
Lakers, who make a blockbuster trade with the Charlotte Hornets on
Wednesday, acquiring Glen Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
One day after signing Rodman, the Lakers fired head coach Del
Harris and hired Rambis. Rodman is being paid of a pro-rated sum
of 468,000 U.S. dollars by the Lakers after making nine million U.
S. dollars last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
