<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, March 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- Despite the devaluation of the local currency and the
reintroduction of a string of export incentives, Zimbabwe's
exports went down by 16 percent in 1998, the Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the devaluation of the Zimbabwean dollar by 60
percent against a basket of other major currencies presented huge
export opportunities. (Zimbabwe-Exports Down)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt witnessed an increase in domestic debts and a
decrease in foreign debts in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending June
30, 1998, an annual report of the Egyptian Central Bank showed
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The domestic debts surged to 136.7 billion Egyptian pounds (40.
21 billion U.S. dollars), a rise of 11.2 billion pounds (3.29
billion dollars), or 8.92 percent, from the 1996-97 fiscal year,
the report said. (Egypt-Debts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- Cement production earned Zambia 62.53 billion kwacha
(over 28.4 million U.S. dollars) with a net profit of 14.283
billion kwacha (about 6.5 million dollars at current rate) in 1998
compared with a net profit of 8.089 billion Kwacha (about 3.7
million dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Chilanga Cement Corporation, overall domestic
sales increased by 1.6 percent in 1998 over 1997, the Zambian News
Agency reported Sunday. (Zambia-Cement-Production ) 
</P>
