<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Likely to Further Relax Imports Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Union government is
likely to further relax its imports limits in its new amendments
to the Export-Import policy to be announced at the end of this
month, a government official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government is slated to liberalize imports of about 400
items by putting them on the open general licence (OGL) list in
the coming Export-Import policy. The items will include
disc-operated record players, tape recorders of certain kinds,
digital loop carrier systems electronic fuses, cookers and kitchen
stoves, picture frames, sinks and wash basins, pocket knives,
soaps, washing preparations, handbags, electrical calculating
machines, etc.
</P>
<P>
Besides, another 250-300 items are expected to be moved from
the restricted to the special import licence (SIL) list.
</P>
<P>
Pressurized by Western countries, India has made a plan to
phase out quantitative restrictions of its imports. The import of
around 740-odd items are to be freed in the first phase of three
years and this is the third year of the first phase. The second
phase is of two years of 2000-2002 and the third phase is one
year-- 2002-2003.
</P>
<P>
Last year India freed 340 import items putting all of them on
the open general licence list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankruptcy Law to Help Spur Economy: Thai Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bankruptcy law, passed by the
Thai Senate last Friday, will help restore commercial banks'
confidence and thus speed up the recovering process in Thai
economy, a senior official of the Bank of Thailand (BOT), the
country's central bank, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
BOT Deputy Governor Kitti Patpongpibul said that with the law,
the pace of financial and corporate restructuring processes would
be quickened as local lenders, namely commercial banks, would be
more willing to extend new loans for businesses due to better
chance of recovering their money.
</P>
<P>
"The law, expected to be implemented by the end of this month,
will help restore and boost lenders' confidence because they
realize that their lending will be protected," he said when asked
to comment on the law.
</P>
<P>
Lenders' great willingness would help hundreds of cash-strapped
businesses to carry on operations and have revenues to repay for
debt services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders here hailed the passage of the bill, saying
that it would not only help raise lenders' confidence, but also
boost foreign investors' sentiment and their willingness to invest
more in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing law, a party that injected fresh funds into
a business that is at risk would not be able to recover the money.
Therefore, few lenders were willing to help troubled clients
though prospects of rehabilitating the business were good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
