<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asian Neurosurgical Society Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Neurosurgical
Society has been formed in Nepal as an effort to strengthen the
region's capability to deal with devastating disorders of the
brain.
</P>
<P>
The society was set up during the first South Asian
Neurosurgical Congress which concluded here Sunday. The three-day
congress was organized by the Nepalese Society of Clinical
Neurosciences under the theme of "regional collaboration in
neurosurgery."
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Neurosurgical Society will soon be registered
as an apex body of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), Dr. Upendra Devkota, chairman of the
organizing committee of the congress, told Xinhua Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nepal now holds the chairmanship of the South Asian
Neurosurgical Society which will be handed over to Bangladesh in
2001 when the country hosts the next regional congress on
neurosurgery in its capital city of Dhaka, he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the first congress as "very, very successful,"
saying that over 130 excellent papers were presented at the
meeting with a full audience all the time.
</P>
<P>
He said work will be done on generating regional cooperation in
research, services, exchange programs and eventually training.
</P>
<P>
"This congress has laid a firm foundation for consolidation and
furtherance of neurosurgical fraternity and successfully
established the conspicuous forum for exchange of the experiences
to harness the future strategy for delivery of effective
neurosurgical service, training and research in the region," the
organizer said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Due to its peculiar socioeconomic and geopolitical situation,
the South Asia region is not optimally equipped in terms of
resources to deal with the devastating disorders of the brain,
Devkota said.
</P>
<P>
He said in Nepal alone, the annual incidence of head injuries
is about 120,000, of which 10 percent are severe.
</P>
<P>
Five of SAARC's seven member countries, Bangladesh, India,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka were represented at the congress
which is also attended by representatives from the United States,
Britain, Germany, Japan, Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan and the Maldives did not take part in the congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
