<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Lowers Overnight Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Board of the
Philippine Central Bank Monday reduced its overnight and other
term rates anew to further the downtrend in domestic interest
rates and encourage greater commercial lending by banks.
</P>
<P>
The move is complemented by the decision of the government to
slash its 5.5-billion-peso (about 137.5 million U.S. dollars)
weekly Treasury-bill offer to around 4 billion pesos (about 100
million dollars), meaning that the fiscal sector is not in dire
need of domestic loans.
</P>
<P>
The two decisions take effect Monday, according to Central Bank
Governor Gabriel Singson and Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu.
</P>
<P>
The overnight borrowing and lending rates now stand at 12.125
percent and 14.125 percent -- down by 12.5 basis points from 12.25
percent and 14.25 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is the second downward adjustment in the overnight and
term rates in just a week's time -- the first one was done in
March 8 this year when the central bank decreased the overnight
rates by 25 basis points.
</P>
<P>
These facilities are used by monetary authorities in either
siphoning off or releasing liquidity into the system to regulate
economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
