<HEADLINE> Thai Police Seizes One Million Amphetamine Pills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai police seized a million
amphetamine pills and arrested two people in one of the biggest
hauls of the illicit drug this year in the northern province of
Chiang Mai, The Nation reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police said they found the pills in a Jeep Cherokee, which
belongs to a senior police officer in the northeastern Mukdahan
province.
</P>
<P>
Name cards of several other police officers were discovered in
the vehicle, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Police intercepted the vehicle at a road check point on Sunday
morning, and used a sniffer dog to search it for drugs. During the
search, police discovered 10 plastic garbage bags containing one
million amphetamine pills.
</P>
<P>
The driver and his companion were arrested by police at the
scene. Police also seized a 9-mm handgun and 12 rounds of
ammunition from the driver.
</P>
<P>
Investors quoted the driver as saying that he had been paid
15,000 baht (405 U.S. dollars) to bring the amphetamines from Mae
Hong Son province to a customer in Chiang Mai, both in the
northern part of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Police estimate the drug haul to be worth 80 million baht (2.2
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
