<HEADLINE> Mindanao Shows Signs of Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The economy in the Philippines'
southern island of Mindanao is showing signs of recovery as the
island's six regions posted lower inflation rates in February this
year, with only two of the regions registering double-digit
inflation rates.
</P>
<P>
Data from the National Statistics Office (NSO) released Sunday
said that inflation rate in the southern island, with a population
of more than 3 million Muslim Filipinos, dropped by 0.4 percent in
February.
</P>
<P>
NSO said the "improving inflation rates of the six regions show
Mindanao is gradually recovering from the economic crisis and the
damage wrought to agriculture and infrastructure because of the
bad weather that stuck Mindanao regions."
</P>
<P>
The drop in inflation rates in all the six Mindanao regions
pulled down the overall rate of Mindanao to 8.8 percent from 9.2
percent registered in January.
</P>
<P>
This rate is also lower than the national inflation rate of 9.9
percent, the NSO said. The national inflation rate in January was
11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The purchasing power of the peso in Mindanao remained at 0.70
peso in February, meaning a basket of goods (and services) worth
70 pesos in 1994 is worth 100 pesos in February 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
