<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fake Seeds Top Rising Complaints from Chinese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Bad and fake seed, poor breeding
stock, inferior chemical fertilizer and farm equipment are the
biggest threats to rural consumers' interests and safety, said a
senior official with the China Consumers Association (CCA).
</P>
<P>
"Our 900 million rural consumers create enormous business
opportunities for manufactures. However, these consumers' rights
have not been properly protected," CCA Secretary-General Yang
Shukun recently said in anticipation of World Consumer Rights Day,
Which is being observed today.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, 30,000 complaints were filed against fake
and shoddy farming products and equipment, CCA statistics
indicated.
</P>
<P>
These complaints represented a 30 percent increase over the
figure the year before, several times the growth in complaints
about other products or services, which averaged 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bad seed, poor breeding stock and inferior chemical fertilizer
have ruthlessly crushed many rural consumers' hopes for harvest.
In some cases, farmers have been left with nothing to live on,
today's China Daily quoted Yang as saying.
</P>
<P>
He voiced grave concerns over roughly manufactured products for
farm use, which pose a direct threat to rural consumers' lives and
health.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 cases of pesticide poisoning are reported every
year. They are often caused by highly toxic farm chemicals leaking
form sub-standard sprayers.
</P>
<P>
With a goal of protecting rural consumers' rights, CCA unveiled
a series of campaigns under the theme "For the Benefits of Rural
Consumers" last January, by conducting a nationwide survey to
assess rural consumers' sense of self-protection and to learn more
about infringements on their rights.
</P>
<P>
Based on the survey results, CCA focused its efforts on
expanding rural consumers' access to quality test and complaint-
handling centers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, village-level complaint-handling centers increased
to 67,123, up 16 percent from 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
