<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Increases Fixed Assets Input through Cutting Red-tapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's oldest special
economic zone, has established a financial system that enables
sustained investment increases for infrastructure construction
with government providing only macro-control and indirect
interference.
</P>
<P>
The city has had 299.5 billion yuan in fixed assets investment
in the past 18 years since the zone was founded, with an annual
growth of 42 percent, with company spending accounting for 60
percent, bank loans for 15 percent, and government spending for
only 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the financial market grew, the city found more ways to
finance by issuing convertible bonds overseas and accumulating
capital on the stock market. The city has one of China's two stock
markets, which has helped get 36.6 billion yuan for Chinese
companies.
</P>
<P>
The city government has changed its role to adapt itself to the
market economy system with Chinese characteristics. It now gives
guidance rather than issuing order on fixed assets development and
has provided a relaxed but orderly financial environment. It
recently cut more than 58 percent of unnecessary red-tapes and is
introducing a public hearing mechanism and consultation into
decision making to improve the transparency of governance. This
has demonstrated its determination keep government apart from
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
