<HEADLINE> More People Escape Poverty In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 15 (Xinhua)-- Nearly 380,000 additional people in
Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have escaped
poverty in the past year, thanks to increased government spending.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang set a poverty line of 670 yuan and it still has over
half a million people below this line. A autonomous regional
government official in the poverty relief office attributes the
success to increased spending by both the central and local
governments last year.
</P>
<P>
The central government allocated 970 million yuan on poverty
relief projects, and local regional government spent additional
200 million yuan, with 90 percent of that going to plants, animal
raising, and infrastructure in mountainous and desert areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 30 poor counties added more than 2,000 km of roads
and most villages have electricity, postal service, and drinking
water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
