<HEADLINE> Highlights of Weekly Trade News in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the trade news
highlights in China between March 8 and 14:
</P>
<P>
-- China will not increase imports of textile machinery in the
next few years, said Chen Bin, an official with the State
Administration of Textile Industry.
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to encourage 50 large and medium-sized
machinery and electronics manufacturers to open plants in Latin
America and Africa to increase exports, Xu Bingjin, assistant
minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said
last Monday in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
-- Microsoft will conduct an extensive test on the Chinese
version of its new business software suite, Office 2000, starting
from March 15. China also signed agreements with the US software
giant in Shenzhen to promote the use of authentic software and
crack down on copyright privacy.
</P>
<P>
-- Chevron, the US oil giant, is to commit 60 million US
dollars in its China upstream operations of oil and gas
exploration and development over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
-- An oil official of China said Wednesday that a great deal
more foreign cooperation is needed to explore for offshore oil and
gas reserves, though the country has already had over 130
contracts with 18 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
-- The MOFTEC announced Wednesday that it will revoke the
import licenses of three more trading companies which have made
illegal payments of large sums of foreign currencies. Thus far, a
total of 11 Chinese trading companies have had their import
licenses revoked because of illegal activities since China began
cracking down on illegal foreign exchange operations last year.
</P>
<P>
-- China opened its first overseas economic zone in Egypt. The
21.85-sq km zone, named China-Egypt Suez Special Economic Zone, is
located in the northwestern part of the Gulf of Suez, 140 km. from
Cairo. The zone is said to have good development prospects because
of convenient transportation and a new deep water port on the Red
Sea.
</P>
<P>
-- The first of what is planned to be an annual spring silk
trade fair opened Thursday in Hangzhou, capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province. Nearly 100 silk enterprises are presenting over
2,000 new products in six varieties such as silk scrolls, garments
and craft works. More than 20 name-brand silk products are on
display.
</P>
<P>
-- China's foreign trade was worth 41.02 billion U.S. dollars
in the first two months of this year, down 4.2 percent from the
same period of last year, according to Chinese Customs officials.
</P>
<P>
Exports for the period were down 10.5 percent and imports were
up 4.7 percent, at 22.39 billion U.S. dollars and 18.63 billion U.
S. dollars, respectively. China's foreign-trade surplus for the
period reached 3.77 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Business licenses of 97 overseas-funded enterprises in
Chongqing Municipality in southwest China have been revoked for
lack of funds, operational sites, and management personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
