<HEADLINE> Computer Centers for Sri Lankan Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will soon set up
computer centers in 100 selected schools islandwide at a cost of
100 million rupees (1.45 million U.S. dollars), the official Daily
News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Education and Higher Education Ministry will select
national schools and leading schools in areas for these centers,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The project aims at introducing computer science to school
children at an early age. While initially it will be taught as an
extra subject, it will be later included in the curriculum as a
compulsory subject.
</P>
<P>
Teachers in the same schools will be trained to work part time
as computer instructors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the World Bank is to fund the project and the
National Institute of Education will design the syllabus which
will cover the fundamentals of computer science including the
operating systems. 
</P>
