<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pests And Plant Disease Plaguing Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The most severe drought in China's
Shaanxi Province in 50 years and warm temperatures have brought
pests and plant disease to a large amount of farmland, posing a
threat to this summer's crops.
</P>
<P>
For the past five months, rainfall in 90 percent of the
province's counties was 80 percent below normal and in most parts
of central and northern Shaanxi, there has not even been a drop of
rain since last autumn.
</P>
<P>
This has caused damage to 400,000 ha. of farmland, according to
local agriculture departments, and an estimated 2.7 million ha. of
farmland and grassland will suffer from pests and disease if the
drought continues and temperatures continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
The dry weather has also caused ecological deterioration in the
province and long-lasting sandstorms have hit the province since
March caused by strong cold winds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
