<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Urged to Avoid Malpractice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Health Minister Zhang
Wenkang has urged to avoid medical malpractice, saying that
frequent instances of medical malpractice have damaged both
patients' health and the reputation of medical profession.
</P>
<P>
The minister admitted that the main causes of medical
malpractice were a lack of strict standards and oversight of
medical practices. In addition, stipulated measures on the
administration of health services have not been fully implemented
in many areas.
</P>
<P>
"Another reason is that some health workers lack a sense of
responsibility and do not understand what it means to provide good
medical services," Zhang was quoted by today's China Daily as
telling a national conference on discipline inspection and
workstyle rectification over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing Second Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress, some deputies have also voiced great concern about how
to avoid and deal with medical malpractice in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"It is imperative for the country to map out the Public Health
Law as a fundamental guide for physicians because the existing
laws and regulations lag behind the rapid development of the
country's market economy," said Zhu Mingde, NPC deputy from
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Practising Physicians which strictly stipulates the
qualifications of physicians will take effect on May 1, this year.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry and other state departments are drafting
additional rules and amendments to the Measures for the Handling
of Medical Accidents which were implemented 12 years ago to make
it more open, scientific and impartial, Zhang Wenkang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
