<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marcoses: Don't Call Our Wealth Ill-Gotten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers of the Marcoses threatened
to file charges against anyone who will persist in calling the
Marcoses' wealth anything but legally-acquired riches, a local
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We will confront these accusers boldly and directly," lawyers
from the Ponce Enrile Reyes and Manalastas law office said Sunday,
the newspaper Today reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by publicist George Balagtas, the lawyers
said "the continuing malicious and wanton misuse of the judicial
process to malign the Marcoses should be stopped now."
</P>
<P>
This came on the eve of the pre-trial hearing of a case before
the Supreme Court which seeks the declaration of Marcos properties
and other assets, including Swiss accounts, as ill-gotten.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said that the decision to take legal action
followed a counterclaim earlier filed by former first lady Imelda
Marcos for the return of a huge block of shares in the Philippine
Long Distance and Telephone Co. and the payment of 20.1 billion
peso (about 502.5 million U.S. dollars) for damages against the
government.
</P>
<P>
"In all civil cases pending against him (and others) before the
Supreme Court, President Marcos is charged, in colorful and
flamboyant rhetoric, with grave abuse of office by obtaining and
accumulating ill-gotten wealth during his incumbency as president
of the Philippines from 1965 onward," Mrs. Marcos said in her
counterclaim.
</P>
<P>
"All enterprises, companies, properties and/or interests
acquired, owned and possessed by President Marcos do not
constitute ill-gotten wealth," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
