<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Unemployment Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China's expanding unemployment
insurance network is expected to cover all the country's 140
million urban employees by June, suggests Ren Zemin, director of
the Ministry of Labor and Social Security's Legal Department.
</P>
<P>
A newly released Regulation on Unemployment Insurance is
expected to encourage a free flow of talent and labor and help
with the reform of State-owned enterprises, today's China's Daily
quoted Ren as saying.
</P>
<P>
The regulation requires urban enterprises and institutions and
their employees to co-establish an unemployment insurance fund,
which also will receive State funding.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises are required to pay 2 percent of their employees'
salaries, while the employees should contribute 1 percent of their
wages to the fund, according to the new regulation.
</P>
<P>
Created in 1986, the unemployment insurance system now covers
79.6 million people, 85.4 percent of whom are working for State
firms, said Mao Jian, director of the ministry's Employment
Department.
</P>
<P>
The country's unemployment rate is unlikely to drop in the
coming few years because the State sector will shed redundant
labors, Ren said.
</P>
<P>
China's registered urban unemployment rate is 3.1 percent. The
figure does not include the 6.09 million laid-off workers who are
being taken care of by re-employment centers set up within their
original enterprises.
</P>
<P>
These centers were introduced earlier as a three-year
transitional shelter for laid-off workers, as China has not had a
sound social insurance system until now, said Mo Rong, associate
professor of the Institute for Labor Studies.
</P>
<P>
The centers pay the laid-off workers a monthly subsidy ranging
form 140 yuan to 380 yuan. The disbursement is paid by the
government, the unemployment insurance fund and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Since the government plans to complete the reform of State-
owned enterprises by 2000, these enterprise-based re-employment
centers are expected to disappear by the end of 2003, Mo said.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers who fail to find a job by that time will get
payments form the unemployment insurance fund for a maximum of two
years, Mo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
