<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Starts Legal Battle to Recover Marcoses' Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government starts
Monday the all-out legal battle with the Marcoses to fulfill the
conditions of the Swiss Federal Supreme Court for the release of
the remaining 440 million U.S. dollars of the recovered 590
million dollar Marcos Swiss deposits.
</P>
<P>
The government is seeking a final and favorable judgment on
Forfeiture Case 0140, which seeks to recover the entire alleged
ill-gotten wealth of the Marcoses and their cronies.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court has set the pretrial hearing of the
eight-year-old case today based on a petition filed last month by
the Presidential Commission on Good Government(PCGG).
</P>
<P>
If it wins the case, not only can the Philippine government get
hold of the 440-million Marcos Swiss deposits, but it can also
recover assets and properties of the Marcoses that have reached an
estimated 5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Armed with evidence proving that the Marcos assets and
properties are ill-gotten and should be returned to the
government, PCGG Chairman Magdangal Elma said he is confident that
the government will win.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Federal Supreme Court, in its rulings in December
1997 and January 1998, ordered the remittance of the 540-million
dollar(now 590 million dollar) Marcos Swiss deposits to the
government and placed it in an escrow account at the Philippine
National Bank (PNB) pending compliance to two conditions.
</P>
<P>
The first condition is the final judgment on Forfeiture Case
0141. The second is fair sharing with the 10,000 victims of
martial law who obtained a 2.35-billion dollar judgment against
the Marcos estate.
</P>
<P>
The government, through an undertaking signed by the PCGG with
PNB officials and lawyers of Marcos foundations, has agreed to
release the 150-million dollar settlement reached by the Marcoses
and the martial-law victims from the escrow account. This fulfills
the second condition set by the Swiss court.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 440 million dollars will be remitted the nation's
coffers if the government can prove that the deposits are
ill-gotten.
</P>
<P>
The case was originally filed by the Solicitor General
Francisco Chavez on December 17, 1991, to recover from the
Marcoses the Swiss accounts as well as assets and properties
totaling 5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
