<HEADLINE> Pakistani Government Welcomes Afghan Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government has
welcomed the agreement reached Sunday in the second round of talks
in Turkmenistan's capital of Ashgabat between the Afghan Taliban
and the opposition Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
"We will lend our full support to its satisfactory
culmination," a Foreign Office spokesman said in a statement
Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan had played behind-the-scene role to promote
the talks between the Afghan warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan remained in touch with the Taliban leadership in
Kandahar to persuade them to send a delegation for talks to the
Turkmenistan capital, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz had two-hour
talks in Islamabad on March 7 with the Taliban's top negotiator
Wakil Ahmed Motawakkil regarding the Ashgabat talks.
</P>
<P>
Motawakkil, a close aide of the Taliban's Supreme Commander
Mullah Muhammad Omar, led his side at the three-day talk in
Ashgabat with Muhammad Younas Qanouni, political advisor of main
opposition commander Ahmed Shah Masood, and his team.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of the Afghan factions made a major
breakthrough in their talks Sunday, agreeing to form a shared
executive, a shared legislature and a shared judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The two sides decided to continue their peace talks in order to
address the rest of the issues and to implement the decisions
already reached. The next round of talks is scheduled to be held
inside Afghanistan at a mutually-agreed venue as soon as
practicable.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to release 20 prisoners each as soon as
possible through the International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
