<HEADLINE> Blair, Clinton Discuss Northern Ireland by Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and U.S. President Bill Clinton Sunday discussed the situation in
Northern Ireland by telephone, British officials said.
</P>
<P>
The talks came ahead of Clinton's meetings this week with the
leaders in Northern Ireland, which are scheduled to be held at St.
Patrick's Day celebrations in Washington.
</P>
<P>
British government officials hope that Clinton can help to end
a row over Irish Republican Army guns that is blocking progress on
Northern Ireland's peace pact.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister gave his assessment of the situation in
advance of the president's meetings this week in Washington with
some of the key players," a Downing Street spokesman told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister said the president could have a real
influence. President Clinton, as ever, said he would do what he
could," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair said it was important that the governments in Britain,
Ireland and the United States worked together closely in this
"vital" stage of the Northern Ireland peace process, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on Kosovo and the Middle
East peace process during their 20-minute conversation, he said.
</P>
