<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Planes Again Attack Positions in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. combat planes Sunday again
attacked military positions in northern Iraq and west of Mosul,
according to U.S. military officials in the German town of
Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
The pilots had noticed Iraq flak fire and had acted "in
self-defense," the U.S. command in Stuttgart said. It said the
planes, using laser-guided bombs, attacked artillery and radar
installations.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi military spokesman said that the U.S. air activity
over northern Iraq lasted for two hours between 0900 GMT and 1100
GMT and involved strikes on "service installations and air defense
positions," according to reports of the German Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the raiding planes were "engaged" by Iraqi
positions and eventually "forced to flee back to their bases in
Turkey" after undertaking 22 sorties over Dhok, Irbil and Mosul.
</P>
<P>
At 1245 GMT, U.S. aircraft backed by British Tornado planes
undertook 76 forays in southern Iraq over a period of 45 minutes
and were engaged by air defense including ground-to-air missile
positions, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the planes which flew in from bases in Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait bombed "service installations and air defense
positions" in al Muthanna governorate.
</P>
<P>
On Friday. U.S. combat planes also attacked Iraqi military
positions in northern Iraq in "self-defense" after they were
detected by Iraqi radar, U.S. air force officials said. Neither
Iraq nor the U.S. have given any accounts or estimates of damage
or casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
