<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Prison Population Doubles Over Past 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of U.S. adults
imprisoned has more than doubled over the past 12 years, reaching
its highest level ever last year, the Justice Department said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At mid-1998, jails and prisons held an estimated 1.8 million
people, according to a Bureau of Justice Statistics report. At the
end of 1985, the figure was 744,208.
</P>
<P>
Viewed another way, there were 668 inmates for every 100,000
U.S. residents as of June 1998, compared with 313 inmates per
100,000 people in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The number of people imprisoned in the United States has grown
for more than a quarter century, helped by increased drug
prosecutions and a general get-tough policy on all classes of
offenders.
</P>
<P>
More criminals serving longer sentences led the inmate
population to top 1 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
About two-thirds of the nation's inmates are in state and
federal prisons; the remaining one-third are in local jails.
</P>
<P>
In the June 1998 Justice Department survey, 1.2 million people
were held in prisons, while local jails held about 600,000 men and
women. Local jails also supervised more than 72,000 people under
various outside work, treatment or home detention programs.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed the total number of people behind bars grew
by 4.4 percent from June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Between the end of 1990 and mid-1998, the incarcerated
population grew an average 6.2 percent annually, said the report's
author, statistician Darrell Gilliard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. AIDS Researcher Gets Germany's Top Medicine Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. AIDS researcher Robert C. Gallo
received Sunday the German most prestigious medicine prize, the
1999 Paul Erlich and Ludwig Darmstaedter Prize.
</P>
<P>
Gallo, discoverer of the AIDS virus with French colleague Luc
Montaigner, received the prize at a ceremony in Frankfurt's St
Paul's Church from Werner Meissner, chairman of the award
committee of the Paul Ehrlich Foundation, and German Health
Minister Andrea Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Gallo was awarded the prize for his discovery in the early
1980s of so-called retro-viruses, which cause serious illness in
humans. The discovery paved the way to the discovery of the AIDS
virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990315.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Delegate: NATO Cannot Be in Kosovo Unless Invited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The chief delegate of the Serbian
delegation to the talks on Kosovo, Ratko Markovic, said Sunday in
Paris that Belgrade was opposed to the deployment of a
multinational force in Kosovo without an invitation.
</P>
<P>
"If NATO comes to Serbia without invitation, it will be
considered a kind of invader and enemy. Yugoslavia has the
legitimate right of defense," he said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign troops could not come to Kosovo unless
Serbia does not have sovereignty over the province.
</P>
<P>
"Since we are a sovereign state, that cannot be done except
with an invitation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Markovic, who is vice prime minister of the Serbian Republic,
said that a presence of foreign force would mean that Kosovo was
an independent state and that Belgrade would lose all political
control over the province if it allowed that.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Yugoslavia would make a distinction between
political agreement and occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian delegation arrived in Paris Sunday to participate
in the new conference on Kosovo which will start Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
